{"title_page": "Federico Morlacchi", "text_new": "{{short description|Italian Paralympic swimmer}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name = Federico Morlacchi\n| nickname = Morlacci{{efn|due to foreign speakers who do not always pronounce his last name correctly}}\n| headercolor= \n| image = \n| imagesize =\n| caption = \n| nationality = [[Italy|Italian]]\n| sport = [[Paralympic swimming]]\n| disability       = Unilateral below the elbow upper limb amputations\n| disability_class = \tS9, SB8, SM9\n| origin = \tCongenital\n| event = \n| club = Polha Varese\n| coach = Massimiliano Tosin\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1993|11|11}}\n| birth_place =  [[Luino]], [[Italy]]\n| residence = \n| retired= \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| height = \n| weight = \n| pb = \n| country = {{ITA}}\n| medaltemplates=\n{{MedalCount\n|[[Summer Paralympic Games|Paralympic Games]]|1|3|3\n|[[Paralympic swimming|World Championships]]|2|4|1\n|[[IPC Swimming European Championships|European Championships]]|10|2|3\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Federico Morlacchi''' (born 11 November 1993 in [[Luino]]) is a male Italian [[Paralympic swimming|paralympic swimmer]].\n\n==Biography==\nHe is boyfriend of the Italian [[paralympic swimming|paralympic swimmer]] [[Giulia Ghiretti]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lastampa.it/2016/09/13/sport/morlacchighiretti-fidanzati-azzurri-insieme-sul-podio-PZYSmkXLBZ2Wyr9oLG2RNJ/premium.html|language=italian|title=Paralimpiadi: Morlacchi-Ghiretti, la super coppia azzurra da podio|publisher=lastampa.it|accessdate=19 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Achievements==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=70% style=\"font-size:90%; text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!Year !!Competition !!Venue !!Position !!Event !!Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=3|2012\n| rowspan=3 align=left|[[2012 Summer Paralympics|Paralympics Games]]\n| rowspan=3 align=left|{{flagicon|GBR}} [[London]] \n| bgcolor=cc9966|3rd\n| [[Swimming at the 2012 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Men's 100 metre butterfly S9|100 m butterfly S9]]\n| \n|-\n| bgcolor=cc9966|3rd\n| [[Swimming at the 2012 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Men's 400 metre freestyle S9|400 m freestyle S9]]\n|\n|-\n| bgcolor=cc9966|3rd\n| [[Swimming at the 2012 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Men's 200 metre individual medley SM9|200 m individual medley SM9]]\n|-\n| rowspan=4|2016\n| rowspan=4 align=left|[[2016 Summer Paralympics|Paralympics Games]]\n| rowspan=4 align=left|{{flagicon|BRA}} [[Rio de Janeiro]] \n| bgcolor=gold|1st\n| 200 m individual medley SM9\n| \n|-\n| bgcolor=silver|2nd\n| [[Swimming at the 2016 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Men's 400 metre freestyle#S9|400 m freestyle S9]]\n|\n|-\n| bgcolor=silver|2nd\n| 100 m butterfly S9\n|\n|-\n| bgcolor=silver|2nd\n| 100 m breaststroke SB8\n|-\n| rowspan=5|2015\n| rowspan=3 align=left|[[2015 IPC Swimming World Championships|World Championships]]\n| rowspan=3 align=left|{{flagicon|GBR}} [[Glasgow]] \n| bgcolor=gold|1st\n| [[2015 IPC Swimming World Championships \u2013 Men's 200 metre individual medley]]\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Italy at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n*[[Italy at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IPC athlete|id=federico-morlacchi|old_id=851822}}\n* {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170305014522/http://www.finp.it/page.php?id=50 |title=Federico Morlacchi at ''Federazione Italiana Nuoto Paralimpico'' (FINP)}} {{in lang|it}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Morlacchi, Federico}}\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Paralympic swimmers of Italy]]\n[[Category:Paralympic gold medalists for Italy]]\n[[Category:Paralympic silver medalists for Italy]]\n[[Category:Paralympic bronze medalists for Italy]]\n[[Category:S9-classified Paralympic swimmers]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Italian Paralympic swimmer}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name = Federico Morlacchi\n| nickname = Morlacci<ref>due to foreign speakers who do not always pronounce his last name correctly</ref>\n| headercolor= \n| image = \n| imagesize =\n| caption = \n| nationality = [[Italy|Italian]]\n| sport = [[Paralympic swimming]]\n| disability       = Unilateral below the elbow upper limb amputations\n| disability_class = \tS9, SB8, SM9\n| origin = \tCongenital\n| event = \n| club = Polha Varese\n| coach = Massimiliano Tosin\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1993|11|11}}\n| birth_place =  [[Luino]], [[Italy]]\n| residence = \n| retired= \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| height = \n| weight = \n| pb = \n| country = {{ITA}}\n| medaltemplates=\n{{MedalCount\n|[[Summer Paralympic Games|Paralympic Games]]|1|3|3\n|[[Paralympic swimming|World Championships]]|2|4|1\n|[[IPC Swimming European Championships|European Championships]]|10|2|3\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Federico Morlacchi''' (born 11 November 1993 in [[Luino]]) is a male Italian [[Paralympic swimming|paralympic swimmer]].\n\n==Biography==\nHe is boyfriend of the Italian [[paralympic swimming|paralympic swimmer]] [[Giulia Ghiretti]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lastampa.it/2016/09/13/sport/morlacchighiretti-fidanzati-azzurri-insieme-sul-podio-PZYSmkXLBZ2Wyr9oLG2RNJ/premium.html|language=italian|title=Paralimpiadi: Morlacchi-Ghiretti, la super coppia azzurra da podio|publisher=lastampa.it|accessdate=19 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Achievements==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=70% style=\"font-size:90%; text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!Year !!Competition !!Venue !!Position !!Event !!Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=3|2012\n| rowspan=3 align=left|[[2012 Summer Paralympics|Paralympics Games]]\n| rowspan=3 align=left|{{flagicon|GBR}} [[London]] \n| bgcolor=cc9966|3rd\n| [[Swimming at the 2012 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Men's 100 metre butterfly S9|100 m butterfly S9]]\n| \n|-\n| bgcolor=cc9966|3rd\n| [[Swimming at the 2012 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Men's 400 metre freestyle S9|400 m freestyle S9]]\n|\n|-\n| bgcolor=cc9966|3rd\n| [[Swimming at the 2012 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Men's 200 metre individual medley SM9|200 m individual medley SM9]]\n|-\n| rowspan=4|2016\n| rowspan=4 align=left|[[2016 Summer Paralympics|Paralympics Games]]\n| rowspan=4 align=left|{{flagicon|BRA}} [[Rio de Janeiro]] \n| bgcolor=gold|1st\n| 200 m individual medley SM9\n| \n|-\n| bgcolor=silver|2nd\n| [[Swimming at the 2016 Summer Paralympics \u2013 Men's 400 metre freestyle#S9|400 m freestyle S9]]\n|\n|-\n| bgcolor=silver|2nd\n| 100 m butterfly S9\n|\n|-\n| bgcolor=silver|2nd\n| 100 m breaststroke SB8\n|-\n| rowspan=5|2015\n| rowspan=3 align=left|[[2015 IPC Swimming World Championships|World Championships]]\n| rowspan=3 align=left|{{flagicon|GBR}} [[Glasgow]] \n| bgcolor=gold|1st\n| [[2015 IPC Swimming World Championships \u2013 Men's 200 metre individual medley]]\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Italy at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n*[[Italy at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IPC athlete|851822}}\n* [http://www.finp.it/page.php?id=50 Athlete profile] at [[:it:Federazione Italiana Nuoto Paralimpico|FINP]] web site\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Morlacchi, Federico}}\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Paralympic swimmers of Italy]]\n[[Category:Paralympic gold medalists for Italy]]\n[[Category:Paralympic silver medalists for Italy]]\n[[Category:Paralympic bronze medalists for Italy]]\n[[Category:S9-classified Paralympic swimmers]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2016 Summer Paralympics]]\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update IPC external link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Federico_Morlacchi"}
{"title_page": "Hripsime Djanpoladjian", "text_new": "{{short description|Russian Armenian archaeologist}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Hripsime Djanpoladjian\n| image              = Hripsime_Djanpoladjian.jpg\n| birth_date         = 26 August 1928\n| birth_place        = Armenia\n| death_date         = 1 September 2004\n| death_place        = St Petersburg, Russia\n| resting_place      = Smolensk Cemetery\n| citizenship        = Armenian {{flagicon|Armenia}}\n| alma_mater         = Yevan State University\n| occupation         = Archaeologist\n| spouse             = Boris Piotrovsky\n| children           = Mikhail Piotrovsky\n}}\n\n'''Hripsime Djanpoladjian,''' Cyrillic: '''\u0420\u0438\u043f\u0441\u0438\u043c\u044d \u041c\u0438\u043a\u0430\u044d\u043b\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0430 \u0414\u0436\u0430\u043d\u043f\u043e\u043b\u0430\u0434\u044f\u043d-\u041f\u0438\u043e\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f''', Armenian: '''\u0540\u057c\u056b\u0583\u057d\u056b\u0574\u0565 \u054b\u0561\u0576\u0583\u0578\u056c\u0561\u0564\u0575\u0561\u0576''' (26 August 1918 - 1 September 2004) was an archaeologist and epigrapher originally from [[Armenia]]. \n\n== Biography ==\n\nDjanpoladjian was born in 1918 on the way to [[Tbilisi]], as her family fled from the [[Armenian Genocide|Armenian genocide]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bvahan.com/RubenAngaladian/works.asp?c_cat=3&c_publ=647|title=Ruben Angaladian|website=www.bvahan.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> Her parents were Michael and Iranianak,<ref name=\":0\" /> who already had a son Gurgen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://auroraprize.com/ru/stories/detail/premium/8805/-|title=\u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0438\u043b \u041f\u0438\u043e\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 - \u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044e \u0436\u0438\u0437\u043d\u0438 \u0447\u0438\u0442\u0430\u0442\u044c \u0442\u0443\u0442|website=AURORA PRIZE|language=ru|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> The family were wealthy and their money came Nakhichevan salt mines.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAfter the establishment of Soviet power in Armenia, the family moved to [[Yerevan]]. After finishing school, Djanpoladjian chose to study archaeology at Yerevan State University.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.museum.ru/n19214|title=\u0421\u043a\u043e\u043d\u0447\u0430\u043b\u0430\u0441\u044c \u0420\u0438\u043f\u0441\u0438\u043c\u044d \u0414\u0436\u0430\u043d\u043f\u043e\u043b\u0430\u0434\u044f\u043d-\u041f\u0438\u043e\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f|website=www.museum.ru|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> After graduation in 1940,<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=|title=Hripsime Janpoladyan's 100th Birthday|url=http://hpj.asj-oa.am/6491/1/286.pdf|journal=Historical-Philological Magazine|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> she took part in excavations at the Karmir-Blur hill of the [[Teishebaini]] fortress city.<ref name=\":1\" /> During these excavations she met her future husband, [[Boris Piotrovsky]].<ref name=\":1\" /> Djanpoladjian had excavated a figurine of the [[Urartu|Urartian]] god of war, a culture which became Piotrovsky's specialism.<ref name=\":1\" /> They married in Yerevan in 1944, and their son [[Mikhail Piotrovsky]] was born there.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nAfter a long illness, Djanpoladjian died in 2004 and was buried in [[Smolensky Cemetery|Smolensk Cemetery]] next to her husband.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://funeral-spb.narod.ru/necropols/smolenskoep/tombs/piotrovsky/piotrovsky.html|title=\u041f\u0418\u041e\u0422\u0420\u041e\u0412\u0421\u041a\u0418\u0419 \u0411\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0441 \u0411\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 (1908-1990)|website=funeral-spb.narod.ru|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nDjanpoladjian graduated with a doctorate in archaeology in 1948 entitled \u201c[[Mkhitar Gosh]] and the Monastery of Nor Getik\", which examined many of the inscriptions there.<ref name=\":2\" /> This interest in epigraphy was to continue; by 1977 she and Suren Avagyan published a new catalogue of Armenian inscriptions.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://haygirk.nla.am/cgi-bin/koha/opac-detail.pl?biblionumber=116956&query_desc=au:%22%D5%8B%D5%A1%D5%B6%D6%83%D5%B8%D5%AC%D5%A1%D5%A4%D5%B5%D5%A1%D5%B6,%20%D5%80%D5%BC%D5%AB%D6%83%D5%BD%D5%AB%D5%B4%D5%A5%20%D5%84%D5%AB%D6%84%D5%A1%D5%B5%D5%A5%D5%AC%D5%AB%22|title=\u0534\u056b\u057e\u0561\u0576 \u0570\u0561\u0575 \u057e\u056b\u0574\u0561\u0563\u0580\u0578\u0582\u0569\u0575\u0561\u0576 \u0589: \u054a\u0580. 6-\u0580\u0564 \u0589 \u053b\u057b\u0587\u0561\u0576\u056b \u0577\u0580\u057b\u0561\u0576|date=1977|publisher=\u0540\u054d\u054d\u0540 \u0533\u0531 \u0570\u0580\u0561\u057f|editor-last=\u0531\u057e\u0561\u0563\u0575\u0561\u0576|editor-first=\u054d\u0578\u0582\u0580\u0565\u0576 \u0531\u0580\u057f\u0565\u0574\u056b|location=\u0535\u0580\u0587\u0561\u0576 \u0589|editor-last2=\u054b\u0561\u0576\u0583\u0578\u056c\u0561\u0564\u0575\u0561\u0576|editor-first2=\u0540\u057c\u056b\u0583\u057d\u056b\u0574\u0565 \u0544\u056b\u0584\u0561\u0575\u0565\u056c\u056b|editor-last3=\u0540\u0576\u0561\u0563\u056b\u057f\u0578\u0582\u0569\u0575\u0561\u0576 \u0587 \u0561\u0566\u0563\u0561\u0563\u0580\u0578\u0582\u0569\u0575\u0561\u0576 \u056b\u0576\u057d\u057f\u056b\u057f\u0578\u0582\u057f \u0540\u054d\u054d\u0540 \u0533\u0531}}</ref> She worked for the Institute of Archeology of the Academy of Arts of the USSR and in the East Department of the Hermitage Museum.<ref name=\":1\" /> In addition to her own research into medieval Armenia, she also edited all of her husband's publications, including an encyclopedic history of the Hermitage, his diaries, travel notes and autobiography.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Dvin Excavations ===\nDjanpoladjian's work on the 1951 [[Dvin (ancient city)|Dvin]] Excavations demonstrated that it was an important centre for medieval glass production.<ref name=\":2\" /> This work developed into an exploration of the glass industry in Dvin from the ninth to thirteenth centuries, with particular focus on trade with the Middle East.<ref>{{Cite book|last=\u054b\u0561\u0576\u0583\u0578\u056c\u0561\u0564\u0575\u0561\u0576|first=\u0540\u057c\u056b\u0583\u057d\u056b\u0574\u0565 \u0544\u056b\u0584\u0561\u0575\u0565\u056c\u056b|url=http://haygirk.nla.am/cgi-bin/koha/opac-detail.pl?biblionumber=49536&query_desc=au:%22%D5%8B%D5%A1%D5%B6%D6%83%D5%B8%D5%AC%D5%A1%D5%A4%D5%B5%D5%A1%D5%B6,%20%D5%80%D5%BC%D5%AB%D6%83%D5%BD%D5%AB%D5%B4%D5%A5%20%D5%84%D5%AB%D6%84%D5%A1%D5%B5%D5%A5%D5%AC%D5%AB%22|title=\u0534\u057e\u056b\u0576\u056b \u0574\u056b\u057b\u0576\u0561\u0564\u0561\u0580\u0575\u0561\u0576 \u0561\u057a\u0561\u056f\u056b\u0576 IX-XIII \u0564\u0564. =: \u0421\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043d\u0435\u0432\u0435\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0435 \u0441\u0442\u0435\u043a\u043b\u043e \u0414\u0432\u0438\u043d\u0430 IX-XIII \u0432\u0432|date=1974|publisher=\u0540\u054d\u054d\u0540 \u0533\u0531 \u0570\u0580\u0561\u057f\u0561\u0580\u0561\u056f\u0579\u0578\u0582\u0569\u0575\u0578\u0582\u0576|others=\u0540\u054d\u054d\u0540 \u0533\u0531\u0531|editor-last=\u0531\u057c\u0561\u0584\u0565\u056c\u0575\u0561\u0576|editor-first=\u0532\u0561\u0562\u056f\u0565\u0576 \u0546\u056b\u056f\u0578\u056c\u0561\u0575\u056b|series=\u0540\u0561\u0575\u0561\u057d\u057f\u0561\u0576\u056b \u0570\u0576\u0561\u0563\u056b\u057f\u0561\u056f\u0561\u0576 \u0570\u0578\u0582\u0577\u0561\u0580\u0571\u0561\u0576\u0576\u0565\u0580\u0568 \u2116 7|location=\u0535\u0580\u0587\u0561\u0576}}</ref> She was able to demonstrate that Armenian craftsmen were copying Syrian glassware.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.armmuseum.ru/news-blog/2018/10/18/-nbsp-piotrovsky|title=\u00ab\u0414\u0432\u043e\u0440 \u0443 \u043d\u0430\u0441 \u0431\u044b\u043b \u0447\u0443\u0434\u0435\u0441\u043d\u044b\u0439\u00bb: \u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0438\u043b \u041f\u0438\u043e\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043e \u0434\u0435\u0442\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435 \u0432 \u0415\u0440\u0435\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0435|website=\u0410\u0440\u043c\u044f\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043c\u0443\u0437\u0435\u0439 \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u044b \u0438 \u043a\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0443\u0440\u044b \u043d\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0439|language=ru-RU|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><gallery>\nFile:Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-F078401-0011, Boris Borissowitsch Piotrowskij.jpg|Husband: Boris Piotrovsky\nFile:Mikhail Piotrovsky - 2018 - 07.jpg|Son: Mikhail Piotrovsky\nFile:Karmir Blur Town.JPG|Karmir Blur Town\nFile:KarmirBlurGod01.jpg|Karmir Blur Idol\nFile:Mkhitar Gosh grave.jpg|Mkhitar Gosh's Grave\nFile:The ruins of Ancient Dvin 19.jpg|Ruins of Dvin, 2019\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{Authority Control}}\n[[Category:1918 births]]\n[[Category:2004 deaths]]\n[[Category:Women archaeologists]]\n[[Category:Armenian women by occupation]]\n[[Category:Epigraphers]]\n[[Category:Archaeologists by nationality]]\n[[Category:Medieval archaeologists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Russian Armenian archaeologist}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Hripsime Djanpoladjian\n| image              = Hripsime_Djanpoladjian.jpg\n| birth_date         = 26 August 1928\n| birth_place        = Armenia\n| death_date         = 1 September 2004\n| death_place        = St Petersburg, Russia\n| resting_place      = Smolensk Cemetery\n| citizenship        = Armenian {{flagicon|Armenia}}\n| alma_mater         = Yevan State University\n| occupation         = Archaeologist\n| spouse             = Boris Piotrovsky\n| children           = Mikhail Piotrovsky\n}}\n\n'''Hripsime Djanpoladjian,''' Cyrillic: '''\u0420\u0438\u043f\u0441\u0438\u043c\u044d \u041c\u0438\u043a\u0430\u044d\u043b\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0430 \u0414\u0436\u0430\u043d\u043f\u043e\u043b\u0430\u0434\u044f\u043d-\u041f\u0438\u043e\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f''', Armenian: '''\u0540\u057c\u056b\u0583\u057d\u056b\u0574\u0565 \u054b\u0561\u0576\u0583\u0578\u056c\u0561\u0564\u0575\u0561\u0576''' (26 August 1918 - 1 September 2004) was an archaeologist and epigrapher originally from [[Armenia]]. \n\n== Biography ==\n\nDjanpoladjian was born in 1918 on the way to [[Tbilisi]], as her family fled from the [[Armenian Genocide|Armenian genocide]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bvahan.com/RubenAngaladian/works.asp?c_cat=3&c_publ=647|title=Ruben Angaladian|website=www.bvahan.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> Her parents were Michael and Iranianak,<ref name=\":0\" /> who already had a son Gurgen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://auroraprize.com/ru/stories/detail/premium/8805/-|title=\u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0438\u043b \u041f\u0438\u043e\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 - \u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044e \u0436\u0438\u0437\u043d\u0438 \u0447\u0438\u0442\u0430\u0442\u044c \u0442\u0443\u0442|website=AURORA PRIZE|language=ru|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> The family were wealthy and their money came Nakhichevan salt mines.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAfter the establishment of Soviet power in Armenia, the family moved to [[Yerevan]]. After finishing school, Djanpoladjian chose to study archaeology at Yerevan State University.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.museum.ru/n19214|title=\u0421\u043a\u043e\u043d\u0447\u0430\u043b\u0430\u0441\u044c \u0420\u0438\u043f\u0441\u0438\u043c\u044d \u0414\u0436\u0430\u043d\u043f\u043e\u043b\u0430\u0434\u044f\u043d-\u041f\u0438\u043e\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f|website=www.museum.ru|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> After graduation in 1940,<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=|title=Hripsime Janpoladyan's 100th Birthday|url=http://hpj.asj-oa.am/6491/1/286.pdf|journal=Historical-Philological Magazine|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> she took part in excavations at the Karmir-Blur hill of the [[Teishebaini]] fortress city.<ref name=\":1\" /> During these excavations she met her future husband, [[Boris Piotrovsky]].<ref name=\":1\" /> Djanpoladjian had excavated a figurine of the [[Urartu|Urartian]] god of war, a culture which became Piotrovsky's specialism.<ref name=\":1\" /> They married in Yerevan in 1944, and their son [[Mikhail Piotrovsky]] was born there.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nAfter a long illness, Djanpoladjian died in 2004 and was buried in [[Smolensky Cemetery|Smolensk Cemetery]] next to her husband.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://funeral-spb.narod.ru/necropols/smolenskoep/tombs/piotrovsky/piotrovsky.html|title=\u041f\u0418\u041e\u0422\u0420\u041e\u0412\u0421\u041a\u0418\u0419 \u0411\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0441 \u0411\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 (1908-1990)|website=funeral-spb.narod.ru|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nDjanpoladjian graduated with a doctorate in archaeology in 1948 entitled \u201c[[Mkhitar Gosh]] and the Monastery of Nor Getik\", which examined many of the inscriptions there.<ref name=\":2\" /> This interest in epigraphy was to continue; by 1977 she and Suren Avagyan published a new catalogue of Armenian inscriptions.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://haygirk.nla.am/cgi-bin/koha/opac-detail.pl?biblionumber=116956&query_desc=au:%22%D5%8B%D5%A1%D5%B6%D6%83%D5%B8%D5%AC%D5%A1%D5%A4%D5%B5%D5%A1%D5%B6,%20%D5%80%D5%BC%D5%AB%D6%83%D5%BD%D5%AB%D5%B4%D5%A5%20%D5%84%D5%AB%D6%84%D5%A1%D5%B5%D5%A5%D5%AC%D5%AB%22|title=\u0534\u056b\u057e\u0561\u0576 \u0570\u0561\u0575 \u057e\u056b\u0574\u0561\u0563\u0580\u0578\u0582\u0569\u0575\u0561\u0576 \u0589: \u054a\u0580. 6-\u0580\u0564 \u0589 \u053b\u057b\u0587\u0561\u0576\u056b \u0577\u0580\u057b\u0561\u0576|date=1977|publisher=\u0540\u054d\u054d\u0540 \u0533\u0531 \u0570\u0580\u0561\u057f|editor-last=\u0531\u057e\u0561\u0563\u0575\u0561\u0576|editor-first=\u054d\u0578\u0582\u0580\u0565\u0576 \u0531\u0580\u057f\u0565\u0574\u056b|location=\u0535\u0580\u0587\u0561\u0576 \u0589|editor-last2=\u054b\u0561\u0576\u0583\u0578\u056c\u0561\u0564\u0575\u0561\u0576|editor-first2=\u0540\u057c\u056b\u0583\u057d\u056b\u0574\u0565 \u0544\u056b\u0584\u0561\u0575\u0565\u056c\u056b|editor-last3=\u0540\u0576\u0561\u0563\u056b\u057f\u0578\u0582\u0569\u0575\u0561\u0576 \u0587 \u0561\u0566\u0563\u0561\u0563\u0580\u0578\u0582\u0569\u0575\u0561\u0576 \u056b\u0576\u057d\u057f\u056b\u057f\u0578\u0582\u057f \u0540\u054d\u054d\u0540 \u0533\u0531}}</ref> She worked for the Institute of Archeology of the Academy of Arts of the USSR and in the East Department of the Hermitage Museum.<ref name=\":1\" /> In addition to her own research into medieval Armenia, she also edited all of her husband's publications, including an encyclopedic history of the Hermitage, his diaries, travel notes and autobiography.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Dvin Excavations ===\nDjanpoladjian's work on the 1951 [[Dvin (ancient city)|Dvin]] Excavations demonstrated that it was an important centre for medieval glass production.<ref name=\":2\" /> This work developed into an exploration of the glass industry in Dvin from the ninth to thirteenth centuries, with particular focus on trade with the Middle East.<ref>{{Cite book|last=\u054b\u0561\u0576\u0583\u0578\u056c\u0561\u0564\u0575\u0561\u0576|first=\u0540\u057c\u056b\u0583\u057d\u056b\u0574\u0565 \u0544\u056b\u0584\u0561\u0575\u0565\u056c\u056b|url=http://haygirk.nla.am/cgi-bin/koha/opac-detail.pl?biblionumber=49536&query_desc=au:%22%D5%8B%D5%A1%D5%B6%D6%83%D5%B8%D5%AC%D5%A1%D5%A4%D5%B5%D5%A1%D5%B6,%20%D5%80%D5%BC%D5%AB%D6%83%D5%BD%D5%AB%D5%B4%D5%A5%20%D5%84%D5%AB%D6%84%D5%A1%D5%B5%D5%A5%D5%AC%D5%AB%22|title=\u0534\u057e\u056b\u0576\u056b \u0574\u056b\u057b\u0576\u0561\u0564\u0561\u0580\u0575\u0561\u0576 \u0561\u057a\u0561\u056f\u056b\u0576 IX-XIII \u0564\u0564. =: \u0421\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043d\u0435\u0432\u0435\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0435 \u0441\u0442\u0435\u043a\u043b\u043e \u0414\u0432\u0438\u043d\u0430 IX-XIII \u0432\u0432|date=1974|publisher=\u0540\u054d\u054d\u0540 \u0533\u0531 \u0570\u0580\u0561\u057f\u0561\u0580\u0561\u056f\u0579\u0578\u0582\u0569\u0575\u0578\u0582\u0576|others=\u0540\u054d\u054d\u0540 \u0533\u0531\u0531|editor-last=\u0531\u057c\u0561\u0584\u0565\u056c\u0575\u0561\u0576|editor-first=\u0532\u0561\u0562\u056f\u0565\u0576 \u0546\u056b\u056f\u0578\u056c\u0561\u0575\u056b|series=\u0540\u0561\u0575\u0561\u057d\u057f\u0561\u0576\u056b \u0570\u0576\u0561\u0563\u056b\u057f\u0561\u056f\u0561\u0576 \u0570\u0578\u0582\u0577\u0561\u0580\u0571\u0561\u0576\u0576\u0565\u0580\u0568 \u2116 7|location=\u0535\u0580\u0587\u0561\u0576}}</ref> She was able to demonstrate that Armenian craftsmen were copying Syrian glassware.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.armmuseum.ru/news-blog/2018/10/18/-nbsp-piotrovsky|title=\u00ab\u0414\u0432\u043e\u0440 \u0443 \u043d\u0430\u0441 \u0431\u044b\u043b \u0447\u0443\u0434\u0435\u0441\u043d\u044b\u0439\u00bb: \u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0438\u043b \u041f\u0438\u043e\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043e \u0434\u0435\u0442\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435 \u0432 \u0415\u0440\u0435\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0435|website=\u0410\u0440\u043c\u044f\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043c\u0443\u0437\u0435\u0439 \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u044b \u0438 \u043a\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0443\u0440\u044b \u043d\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0439|language=ru-RU|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><gallery>\nFile:Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-F078401-0011, Boris Borissowitsch Piotrowskij.jpg|Husband: Boris Piotrovsky\nFile:Mikhail Piotrovsky - 2018 - 07.jpg|Son: Mikhail Piotrovsky\nFile:Karmir Blur Town.JPG|Karmir Blur Town\nFile:KarmirBlurGod01.jpg|Karmir Blur Idol\nFile:Mkhitar Gosh grave.jpg|Mkhitar Gosh's Grave\nFile:The ruins of Ancient Dvin 19.jpg|Ruins of Dvin, 2019\n</gallery>\n{{Authority Control}}\n== References ==\n<references />\n[[Category:1918 births]]\n[[Category:2004 deaths]]\n[[Category:Women archaeologists]]\n[[Category:Armenian women by occupation]]\n[[Category:Epigraphers]]\n[[Category:Archaeologists by nationality]]\n[[Category:Medieval archaeologists]]\n", "name_user": "Kj cheetham", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor formatting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hripsime_Djanpoladjian"}
{"title_page": "Esher Place", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n'''Esher Place''' is a Grade-II listed<ref>{{NHLE |num=1377431 |accessdate=26 August 2010}}</ref> [[English country house|country house]], since 1953 used as a [[college]] by the [[trade union]] [[Unite the Union|Unite]], in [[Esher]], [[Surrey]], [[United Kingdom]].  The building is at least the fourth on approximately the same site and mainly dates to the 1890s. It incorporates traces and small parts of some its earlier forebears.\n[[File:Rear of Esher Place - geograph.org.uk - 718490.jpg|thumb|200px|right|View of Esher Place today, seen from the west and showing the rear of the house.]]\n\n==History==\nThe first recorded predecessor was acquired by or for [[Peter des Roches]], [[Bishop of Winchester]], for his bishopric, early in the 13th century.  The house was torn down in the latter half of the 15th century by [[William Waynflete]], Bishop of Winchester and [[Lord Chancellor]], to make way for a large brick residence (with a tall slender tower [[gatehouse]] (''Waynflete's Tower'', see below) that stands today).   [[Thomas Wolsey|Cardinal Wolsey]], who possessed Esher Place as Bishop of Winchester, was kept under [[house arrest]] here after his fall from power.  The estate was then seized by [[Henry VIII]], restored to the Bishop of Winchester by [[Mary I of England|Mary I]], and the lease was then re-purchased by the Crown under [[Elizabeth I]], who granted it to her [[List of Lords High Admiral|Lord High Admiral]], [[William Howard, 1st Baron Howard of Effingham|Lord Howard of Effingham]], who granted it to [[Francis Drake|Sir Francis Drake]]'s cousin [[Richard Drake]].  After the defeat of the Spanish Armada, three captured Spanish admirals and their retinue were held at Esher for over five years. It remained in the Drake family until 1634. Over the next 75 years, the house which had more land than today was held by at least seven individuals, the last two being Sir Thomas Lynch, an early [[List of Governors of Jamaica|English governor]] of [[History of Jamaica|Jamaica]], and John Latton, a pluralistic office-holder under [[William III of England|William III]] (William of Orange).\n\n[[File:Esher Place 1737.jpg|thumb|East View of Esher Place, Surrey, England in 1737. A line engraving drawn and engraved by the brothers Samuel and Nathaniel Buck. The print is dated to 1737.]]\n\nIn 1716 its wider agricultural [[estate (land)|estate]] was separated from what was its [[manor]] house, that is, sold to the first [[Thomas Pelham-Holles, 1st Duke of Newcastle|Duke of Newcastle]], who owned [[Claremont (country house)|Claremont]] in the same [[ecclesiastical parish|parish]].  The house (and immediate grounds), passed through two owners, including Peter Delaperte, one of the directors of the [[South Sea Company]], and came into the ownership of the Duke's younger brother, [[Henry Pelham]], in 1729.  Pelham hired [[William Kent]] to renovate the property who did so by having demolished much of the medieval and Tudor portions &mdash; except for the [[Esher Place#Waynflete's Tower|gatehouse]] &mdash; and adding wings and some of the earliest [[Gothic revival]] ornamentation in England.\n\nIn ''[[The Seasons (Thomson poem)|The Seasons]]'', the Scottish poet [[James Thomson (poet)|James Thomson]] (author of the lyrics to ''[[Rule, Britannia!]]'') praises\n\n{{cquote|Esher's peaceful grove/Where Kent and Nature vie for Pelham's love...Where, in the sweetest solitude embraced, by the soft windings of the gentle Mole, from courts and senates Pelham finds repose.\".<ref name=\"Nairn\">Nairn (2002), p. 222-23.</ref>}}  Esher Place's owner's family by owning the house had the privilege of using one half of the [[St. George's Church, Esher#Newcastle Pew|Newcastle Pew]] at [[St. George's Church, Esher]].  After Pelham's death, the property passed to his daughter, and was then purchased in 1805 by London merchant John Spicer.\n\n[[File:West View of Esher Place engraved 1759..jpg|thumb|West View of Esher Place, Surrey 1759, as earlier remodelled by William Kent.]]\n\nSpicer pulled down the house and used the material to build another, designed by [[Edward Lapidge]],<ref>{{cite DNB|wstitle=Lapidge, Edward|last=Cust|first=Lionel Henry|authorlink=|volume=32}}</ref> on a more elevated site. The new house was stuccoed, in imitation of stone, with Ionic porticoes on north and south fronts, and semi-circular wings.<ref>{{cite book |title= Select Illustrations of the County of Surrey|last=Prosser |first=G.F. |year=1828 |publisher= |location=London|page= |pages= |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4PcGAAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover |accessdate=24 July 2011}}</ref> In the late 1890s, this building was then incorporated as a wing into the current [[Ch\u00e2teauesque|French Renaissance style]] house on the site, designed by [[George Thomas Robinson|G.T. Robinson]] and [[Achille Duch\u00eane]] at the behest of [[Edgar Vincent, 1st Viscount D'Abernon|Edgar Vincent]], later 1st Lord D'Abernon.  Vincent had purchased the much-reduced estate in 1895 from [[Money Wigram]], who had bought it from the Spicer heirs.  Vincent &mdash; Lord D'Abernon after 1914 &mdash; had guests including [[Edward VIII]] (the British King in much of the year 1936) when [[Prince of Wales]], [[Cecil Rhodes]], and [[Anna Pavlova]]. However, in 1930 Lord D'Abernon gave the house to the [[Ragged school|Ragged School Union later the Shaftesbury Society]], while most of the grounds were sold to developers who built a housing estate around the mansion.<ref>[http://www.esherplace.com Website] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110202153515/http://www.esherplace.com/ |date=2011-02-02 }} with historical information</ref>  The house became the Shaftesbury Home for young children from 1930 until 1952, when it was sold to the [[Electrical, Electronic, Telecommunications and Plumbing Union|Electrical Trades Union]] (now merged into Unite the Union), which opened it in 1953 as the college it remains today. The gatehouse on Moore Lane can still be seen and is located in [[Lower Green Esher]].\n\n[[File:Esher-Surrey-Waynfletes-Tower.jpg|thumb|220px|right|Waynflete's Tower]]\n\n==Waynflete's Tower==\n{{main|Wayneflete Tower}}\n'''Waynflete's Tower''' ({{coord|51.3738|-0.3768|type:landmark_region:GB|display=inline|name=Waynflete's Tower}}) is a grade-1 listed<ref>{{NHLE |num=1286940 |accessdate=26 August 2010}}</ref> [[gatehouse]], originally built at the same time as the late 15th-century house, but much modified by William Kent following Henry Pelham's purchase of the property.  Kent designed the additions of the two three-bay ranges of three stories to each side and the one-story porch between the turrets with ogee-arched doorway, triple window above with ogee-headed lights (window spaces), and quatrefoil windows.  The rib-vaulted entrance hall was the gateway in Wayneflete's time which Kent had stuccoed or plastered over.<ref name=\"Nairn\">Nairn (2002), p. 222-23.</ref>  The Tower is currently a residence.<ref>[http://www.waynefletetower.com/ Website] for the tower</ref>\n\nWaynflete's Tower was also the subject of a [[Time Team (Series 13)|2006 episode]] of archaeological television programme ''[[Time Team]]''.<ref>[http://www.channel4.com/history/microsites/T/timeteam/2006_esher.html Website] discussing ''Time Team'' investigation</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* Esher Place Training and Conference Center: [https://web.archive.org/web/20110720142050/http://www.unitetheunion.org/pdf/Esher%20History.pdf A History]\n* {{cite book |last1=Nairn|first1=Ian|last2=Pevsner|first2=Nicholas|editor1-first=Bridget|editor1-last=Cherry|title=The Buildings of England: Surrey|edition=Revised 2nd|publisher=Yale University Press|year=2002|isbn=0-300-09675-5}}\n* English Heritage's PastScape [http://www.pastscape.org.uk/hob.aspx?hob_id=397606  website entry]\n\n==External links==\n*http://www.uniteesherplace.org\n*[https://lowergreenesher.co.uk/2019/11/18/esher-place-gatehouse/ Pictures of Esher Place's Former Gatehouse] \n\n{{GeoGroupTemplate}}\n{{Elmbridge}}\n\n{{coord|51.3720|-0.3726|type:landmark_region:GB|display=title|name=Esher Place}}\n\n[[Category:Grade II listed buildings in Surrey]]\n[[Category:Unite the Union]]\n[[Category:Episcopal palaces of the bishops of Winchester]]\n[[Category:Grade II listed houses]]\n[[Category:Country houses in Surrey]]\n[[Category:William Kent buildings]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n'''Esher Place''' is a Grade-II listed<ref>{{NHLE |num=1377431 |accessdate=26 August 2010}}</ref> [[English country house|country house]], since 1953 used as a [[college]] by the [[trade union]] [[Unite the Union|Unite]], in [[Esher]], [[Surrey]], [[United Kingdom]].  The building is at least the fourth on approximately the same site and mainly dates to the 1890s. It incorporates traces and small parts of some its earlier forebears.\n[[File:Rear of Esher Place - geograph.org.uk - 718490.jpg|thumb|200px|right|View of Esher Place today, seen from the west and showing the rear of the house.]]\n\n==History==\nThe first recorded predecessor was acquired by or for [[Peter des Roches]], [[Bishop of Winchester]], for his bishopric, early in the 13th century.  The house was torn down in the latter half of the 15th century by [[William Waynflete]], Bishop of Winchester and [[Lord Chancellor]], to make way for a large brick residence (with a tall slender tower [[gatehouse]] (''Waynflete's Tower'', see below) that stands today).   [[Thomas Wolsey|Cardinal Wolsey]], who possessed Esher Place as Bishop of Winchester, was kept under [[house arrest]] here after his fall from power.  The estate was then seized by [[Henry VIII]], restored to the Bishop of Winchester by [[Mary I of England|Mary I]], and the lease was then re-purchased by the Crown under [[Elizabeth I]], who granted it to her [[List of Lords High Admiral|Lord High Admiral]], [[William Howard, 1st Baron Howard of Effingham|Lord Howard of Effingham]], who granted it to [[Francis Drake|Sir Francis Drake]]'s cousin [[Richard Drake]].  After the defeat of the Spanish Armada, three captured Spanish admirals and their retinue were held at Esher for over five years. It remained in the Drake family until 1634. Over the next 75 years, the house which had more land than today was held by at least seven individuals, the last two being Sir Thomas Lynch, an early [[List of Governors of Jamaica|English governor]] of [[History of Jamaica|Jamaica]], and John Latton, a pluralistic office-holder under [[William III of England|William III]] (William of Orange).\n\n[[File:Esher Place 1737.jpg|thumb|East View of Esher Place, Surrey, England in 1737. A line engraving drawn and engraved by the brothers Samuel and Nathaniel Buck. The print is dated to 1737.]]\n\nIn 1716 its wider agricultural [[estate (land)|estate]] was separated from what was its [[manor]] house, that is, sold to the first [[Thomas Pelham-Holles, 1st Duke of Newcastle|Duke of Newcastle]], who owned [[Claremont (country house)|Claremont]] in the same [[ecclesiastical parish|parish]].  The house (and immediate grounds), passed through two owners, including Peter Delaperte, one of the directors of the [[South Sea Company]], and came into the ownership of the Duke's younger brother, [[Henry Pelham]], in 1729.  Pelham hired [[William Kent]] to renovate the property who did so by having demolished much of the medieval and Tudor portions &mdash; except for the [[Esher Place#Waynflete's Tower|gatehouse]] &mdash; and adding wings and some of the earliest [[Gothic revival]] ornamentation in England.\n\nIn ''[[The Seasons (Thomson poem)|The Seasons]]'', the Scottish poet [[James Thomson (poet)|James Thomson]] (author of the lyrics to ''[[Rule, Britannia!]]'') praises\n\n{{cquote|Esher's peaceful grove/Where Kent and Nature vie for Pelham's love...Where, in the sweetest solitude embraced, by the soft windings of the gentle Mole, from courts and senates Pelham finds repose.\".<ref name=\"Nairn\">Nairn (2002), p. 222-23.</ref>}}  Esher Place's owner's family by owning the house had the privilege of using one half of the [[St. George's Church, Esher#Newcastle Pew|Newcastle Pew]] at [[St. George's Church, Esher]].  After Pelham's death, the property passed to his daughter, and was then purchased in 1805 by London merchant John Spicer.\n\n[[File:West View of Esher Place engraved 1759..jpg|thumb|West View of Esher Place, Surrey 1759, as earlier remodelled by William Kent.]]\n\nSpicer pulled down the house and used the material to build another, designed by [[Edward Lapidge]],<ref>{{cite DNB|wstitle=Lapidge, Edward|last=Cust|first=Lionel Henry|authorlink=|volume=32}}</ref> on a more elevated site. The new house was stuccoed, in imitation of stone, with Ionic porticoes on north and south fronts, and semi-circular wings.<ref>{{cite book |title= Select Illustrations of the County of Surrey|last=Prosser |first=G.F. |year=1828 |publisher= |location=London|page= |pages= |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4PcGAAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover |accessdate=24 July 2011}}</ref> In the late 1890s, this building was then incorporated as a wing into the current [[Ch\u00e2teauesque|French Renaissance style]] house on the site, designed by [[George Thomas Robinson|G.T. Robinson]] and [[Achille Duch\u00eane]] at the behest of [[Edgar Vincent, 1st Viscount D'Abernon|Edgar Vincent]], later 1st Lord D'Abernon.  Vincent had purchased the much-reduced estate in 1895 from [[Money Wigram]], who had bought it from the Spicer heirs.  Vincent &mdash; Lord D'Abernon after 1914 &mdash; had guests including [[Edward VIII]] (the British King in much of the year 1936) when [[Prince of Wales]], [[Cecil Rhodes]], and [[Anna Pavlova]]. However, in 1930 Lord D'Abernon gave the house to the [[Ragged school|Ragged School Union later the Shaftesbury Society]], while most of the grounds were sold to developers who built a housing estate around the mansion.<ref>[http://www.esherplace.com Website] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110202153515/http://www.esherplace.com/ |date=2011-02-02 }} with historical information</ref>  The house became the Shaftesbury Home for young children from 1930 until 1952, when it was sold to the [[Electrical, Electronic, Telecommunications and Plumbing Union|Electrical Trades Union]] (now merged into Unite the Union), which opened it in 1953 as the college it remains today.\n\n[[File:Esher-Surrey-Waynfletes-Tower.jpg|thumb|220px|right|Waynflete's Tower]]\n\n==Waynflete's Tower==\n{{main|Wayneflete Tower}}\n'''Waynflete's Tower''' ({{coord|51.3738|-0.3768|type:landmark_region:GB|display=inline|name=Waynflete's Tower}}) is a grade-1 listed<ref>{{NHLE |num=1286940 |accessdate=26 August 2010}}</ref> [[gatehouse]], originally built at the same time as the late 15th-century house, but much modified by William Kent following Henry Pelham's purchase of the property.  Kent designed the additions of the two three-bay ranges of three stories to each side and the one-story porch between the turrets with ogee-arched doorway, triple window above with ogee-headed lights (window spaces), and quatrefoil windows.  The rib-vaulted entrance hall was the gateway in Wayneflete's time which Kent had stuccoed or plastered over.<ref name=\"Nairn\">Nairn (2002), p. 222-23.</ref>  The Tower is currently a residence.<ref>[http://www.waynefletetower.com/ Website] for the tower</ref>\n\nWaynflete's Tower was also the subject of a [[Time Team (Series 13)|2006 episode]] of archaeological television programme ''[[Time Team]]''.<ref>[http://www.channel4.com/history/microsites/T/timeteam/2006_esher.html Website] discussing ''Time Team'' investigation</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* Esher Place Training and Conference Center: [https://web.archive.org/web/20110720142050/http://www.unitetheunion.org/pdf/Esher%20History.pdf A History]\n* {{cite book |last1=Nairn|first1=Ian|last2=Pevsner|first2=Nicholas|editor1-first=Bridget|editor1-last=Cherry|title=The Buildings of England: Surrey|edition=Revised 2nd|publisher=Yale University Press|year=2002|isbn=0-300-09675-5}}\n* English Heritage's PastScape [http://www.pastscape.org.uk/hob.aspx?hob_id=397606  website entry]\n\n==External links==\n*http://www.uniteesherplace.org\n*[https://lowergreenesher.co.uk/2019/11/18/esher-place-gatehouse/ Pictures of Esher Place's Former Gatehouse] \n\n{{GeoGroupTemplate}}\n{{Elmbridge}}\n\n{{coord|51.3720|-0.3726|type:landmark_region:GB|display=title|name=Esher Place}}\n\n[[Category:Grade II listed buildings in Surrey]]\n[[Category:Unite the Union]]\n[[Category:Episcopal palaces of the bishops of Winchester]]\n[[Category:Grade II listed houses]]\n[[Category:Country houses in Surrey]]\n[[Category:William Kent buildings]]\n", "name_user": "AM-LowerGreenEsher", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:added some info about the gatehouse in Lower Green", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Esher_Place"}
{"title_page": "Australian Mathematical Society", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Primary sources|date=December 2006}}\nThe '''Australian Mathematical Society (AustMS)''' was founded in 1956 and is the national society of the [[mathematics]] profession in [[Australia]]. One of the Society's listed purposes is to promote the cause of mathematics in the community by representing the interests of the profession to government.<ref>[http://www.austms.org.au/About+us About us], www.austms.org.au</ref> The Society also publishes three mathematical journals. Currently, the Society's president is Timothy Marchant.<ref>[http://www.austms.org.au/Office+bearers Officials], www.austms.org.au</ref>\n\n==Society awards==\n* The [[Australian Mathematical Society Medal]]\n* The [[George Szekeres Medal]]\n* The Gavin Brown Prize\n* The Mahler Lectureship\n* The B.H. Neumann Prize\n\n==Society journals==\n* ''Journal of the Australian Mathematical Society'' \n* ''ANZIAM Journal'' (formerly ''Series B, Applied Mathematics'')<ref>[http://www.austms.org.au/ANZIAM+Journal The ANZIAM Journal], www.austms.org.au</ref>\n* ''Bulletin of the Australian Mathematical Society''\n\n==ANZIAM==\n'''ANZIAM''' ('''Australia and New Zealand Industrial and Applied Mathematics''') is a division of The Australian Mathematical Society (AustMS). Members are interested in [[applied mathematical research]], mathematical applications in industry and business, and [[mathematics education]] at tertiary level.<ref>[http://www.anziam.org.au/About+us About us], ANZIAM, www.anziam.org.au</ref>\n\n===ANZIAM awards===\n* The ANZIAM Medal<ref name=ANZIAMMedal>[http://www.anziam.org.au/The+ANZIAM+medal The ANZIAM Medal], www.anziam.org.au</ref>\n* The [[John Henry Michell|J.H. Michell]] Medal<ref>[http://www.anziam.org.au/The+JH+Michell+Medal The JH Michell Medal], www.anziam.org.au</ref>\n* The T.M. Cherry Prize<ref>[http://www.anziam.org.au/The+TM+Cherry+Prize The TM Cherry Prize], www.anziam.org.au</ref>\n\n====The ANZIAM Medal====\nThe ANZIAM medal is awarded on the basis of research achievements, activities enhancing applied or industrial mathematics, or both, and contributions to ANZIAM.<ref name=ANZIAMMedal/>\n*1995 [[Renfrey B. Potts]]<ref>[http://www.anziam.org.au/The+1995+ANZIAM+Medal The 1995 ANZIAM Medal], www.anziam.org.au</ref>\n*1997 [[Ian H. Sloan]]<ref>[http://www.anziam.org.au/The+1997+ANZIAM+Medal The 1997 ANZIAM Medal], www.anziam.org.au</ref>\n*1999 [[Ernest O. Tuck]]<ref>[http://www.anziam.org.au/The+1999+ANZIAM+Medal The 1999 ANZIAM Medal], www.anziam.org.au</ref>\n*2001 [[Charles E. M. Pearce]]<ref>[http://www.anziam.org.au/The+2001+ANZIAM+Medal The 2001 ANZIAM Medal], www.anziam.org.au</ref>\n*2004 Roger H.J. Grimshaw<ref>[http://www.anziam.org.au/The+2004+ANZIAM+Medal The 2004 ANZIAM Medal], www.anziam.org.au</ref>\n*2006 Graeme C. Wake<ref>[http://www.anziam.org.au/The+2006+ANZIAM+Medal The 2006 ANZIAM Medal], www.anziam.org.au</ref>\n*2008 James M. Hill<ref>[http://www.anziam.org.au/The+2008+ANZIAM+Medal The 2008 ANZIAM Medal], www.anziam.org.au</ref>\n*2010 Robert Anderssen<ref>[http://www.anziam.org.au/The+2010+ANZIAM+Medal The 2010 ANZIAM Medal], www.anziam.org.au</ref>\n*2012 Robert McKibbin<ref>[http://www.anziam.org.au/The+2012+ANZIAM+Medal The 2012 ANZIAM Medal], www.anziam.org.au</ref>\n\n===MathSport===\nSince 1992, ANZIAM has organised biennial meetings, initially under the name \u201cMathematics and Computers in Sport Conferences\u201d, and now under the name \"MathSport\".<ref>[http://www.anziam.org.au/MathSport MathSport], www.anziam.org.au</ref> Main topics are mathematical models and computer applications in sports, as well as coaching and teaching methods based on [[informatics]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[American Mathematical Society]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Resources==\n* {{Official website|http://www.austms.org.au/}}\n{{authority control}}\n[[Category:1956 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Mathematical societies]]\n[[Category:Learned societies of Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Primary sources|date=December 2006}}\nThe '''Australian Mathematical Society (AustMS)''' was founded in 1956 and is the national society of the [[mathematics]] profession in [[Australia]]. One of the Society's listed purposes is to promote the cause of mathematics in the community by representing the interests of the profession to government.<ref>[http://www.austms.org.au/About+us About us], www.austms.org.au</ref> The Society also publishes three mathematical journals. Currently, the Society's president is Timothy Marchant.<ref>[http://www.austms.org.au/Office+bearers Officials], www.austms.org.au</ref>\n\n==Society awards==\n* The [[Australian Mathematical Society Medal]]\n* The [[George Szekeres Medal]]\n* The Gavin Brown Prize\n* The Mahler Lectureship\n* The B.H. Neumann Prize\n\n==Society journals==\n* ''Journal of the Australian Mathematical Society'' \n* ''ANZIAM Journal'' (formerly ''Series B, Applied Mathematics'')<ref>[http://www.austms.org.au/ANZIAM+Journal The ANZIAM Journal], www.austms.org.au</ref>\n* ''Bulletin of the Australian Mathematical Society''\n\n==ANZIAM==\n'''ANZIAM''' ('''Australia and New Zealand Industrial and Applied Mathematics''') is a division of The Australian Mathematical Society (AustMS). Members are interested in [[applied mathematical research]], mathematical applications in industry and business, and [[mathematics education]] at tertiary level.<ref>[http://www.anziam.org.au/About+us About us], ANZIAM, www.anziam.org.au</ref>\n\n===ANZIAM awards===\n* The ANZIAM Medal<ref name=ANZIAMMedal>[http://www.anziam.org.au/The+ANZIAM+medal The ANZIAM Medal], www.anziam.org.au</ref>\n* The [[John Henry Michell|J.H. Michell]] Medal<ref>[http://www.anziam.org.au/The+JH+Michell+Medal The JH Michell Medal], www.anziam.org.au</ref>\n* The T.M. Cherry Prize<ref>[http://www.anziam.org.au/The+TM+Cherry+Prize The TM Cherry Prize], www.anziam.org.au</ref>\n\n====The ANZIAM Medal====\nThe ANZIAM medal is awarded on the basis of research achievements, activities enhancing applied or industrial mathematics, or both, and contributions to ANZIAM.<ref name=ANZIAMMedal/>\n*1995 [[Renfrey B. Potts]]<ref>[http://www.anziam.org.au/The+1995+ANZIAM+Medal The 1995 ANZIAM Medal], www.anziam.org.au</ref>\n*1997 [[Ian H. Sloan]]<ref>[http://www.anziam.org.au/The+1997+ANZIAM+Medal The 1997 ANZIAM Medal], www.anziam.org.au</ref>\n*1999 [[Ernest O. Tuck]]<ref>[http://www.anziam.org.au/The+1999+ANZIAM+Medal The 1999 ANZIAM Medal], www.anziam.org.au</ref>\n*2001 [[Charles E. M. Pearce]]<ref>[http://www.anziam.org.au/The+2001+ANZIAM+Medal The 2001 ANZIAM Medal], www.anziam.org.au</ref>\n*2004 Roger H.J. Grimshaw<ref>[http://www.anziam.org.au/The+2004+ANZIAM+Medal The 2004 ANZIAM Medal], www.anziam.org.au</ref>\n*2006 Graeme C. Wake<ref>[http://www.anziam.org.au/The+2006+ANZIAM+Medal The 2006 ANZIAM Medal], www.anziam.org.au</ref>\n*2008 James M. Hill<ref>[http://www.anziam.org.au/The+2008+ANZIAM+Medal The 2008 ANZIAM Medal], www.anziam.org.au</ref>\n*2010 Robert Anderssen<ref>[http://www.anziam.org.au/The+2010+ANZIAM+Medal The 2010 ANZIAM Medal], www.anziam.org.au</ref>\n*2012 Robert McKibbin<ref>[http://www.anziam.org.au/The+2012+ANZIAM+Medal The 2012 ANZIAM Medal], www.anziam.org.au</ref>\n\n===MathSport===\nSince 1992, ANZIAM has organised biennial meetings, initially under the name \u201cMathematics and Computers in Sport Conferences\u201d, and now under the name \"MathSport\".<ref>[http://www.anziam.org.au/MathSport MathSport], www.anziam.org.au</ref> Main topics are mathematical models and computer applications in sports, as well as coaching and teaching methods based on [[informatics]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[American Mathematical Society]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Resources==\n* {{Official website|http://www.austms.org.au/}}\n\n[[Category:1956 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Mathematical societies]]\n[[Category:Learned societies of Australia]]\n", "name_user": "MathXplore", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eResources", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Australian_Mathematical_Society"}
{"title_page": "Lathkill Dale", "text_new": "{{Infobox valley|name=Lathkill Dale|map_alt=|coordinates_ref=<!-- Statistics -->|coordinates={{Coord|53.1846|-1.7639|display=title, inline|type:river}}|label_position=|label=|relief=|location=[[Derbyshire]], [[England]]|elevation=|map_caption=|map_size=|map_image=|photo_caption=View down Lathkill Dale near Monyash|photo_alt=|photo_size=|photo=View down Lathkill Dale near Monyash.jpg|other_name=|elevation_ft=|age=|footnotes=|watercourses=[[River Lathkill]]\n<!-- Below -->|traversed=|towns=|topo=|boundaries=|type=|elevation_m=|depth=|area=|width=|length=|direction=|elevation_ref=|embed=}}\n[[File:River at Lathkill Head Cave.jpg|thumb|292x292px|Lathkill Head Cave in wet conditions]]\n{{Use dmy dates|date = March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n\n'''Lathkill Dale''' is the [[valley]] of the [[River Lathkill]] near [[Bakewell]], [[Derbyshire]] in the [[Peak District]] of England. The river emerges into the dale from springs below Lathkill Head Cave (or, in wet conditions, from the cave itself).\n\n== Nature reserve ==\nThe river valley is part of the [[Derbyshire Dales National Nature Reserve]] and is popular with tourists who visit for its natural environment and wildlife. [[Natural England]] manages the reserve which covers five separate dales of the [[White Peak]] (Lathkill Dale, Cressbrook Dale, Hay Dale, Long Dale and [[Monk's Dale|Monk\u2019s Dale]]).<ref name=\"NNR\">{{cite web|url=http://publications.naturalengland.org.uk/publication/31052?category=23001|title=Derbyshire Dales National Nature Reserve (NE154)|last=|first=|date=18 July 2014|website=|publisher=Natural England|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> The dale includes two [[Site of Special Scientific Interest|Sites of Special Scientific Interest]] (SSSIs) and areas designated as Open Access Land in the [[Countryside and Rights of Way Act 2000]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://designatedsites.naturalengland.org.uk/PDFsForWeb/Citation/1003711.pdf|title=Lathkill Dale|last=|first=|date=1972|website=|publisher=Natural England|type=SSSI citation|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://designatedsites.naturalengland.org.uk/PDFsForWeb/Citation/1003846.pdf|title=Upper Lathkill|last=|first=|date=1989|website=|publisher=Natural England|type=SSSI citation|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nLathkill Dale is known for its range of wildflower species (incuding orchids and the rare [[Polemonium caeruleum|Jacob's ladder]]), butterflies, ancient woodland and the presence of birds of prey, [[White-throated dipper|dippers]], [[Woodpecker|woodpeckers]] and [[European water vole|water voles]].\n\nThe River Lathkill is a [[Winterbourne (stream)|winterbourne stream]] (drying up in sections over summer). After heavy rain, clear river water rises up from sink-holes near [[Over Haddon]] and runs into deep pools known locally as The Blue Waters. Beyond this there are 12 weirs, which were built for trout fishing in [[Victorian era|Victorian]] times.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.peakdistrictonline.co.uk/lathkill-dale-c10113.html|title=Lathkill Dale {{!}} Peak District|last=|first=|date=|website=www.peakdistrictonline.co.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref> In 1653 the poet and angler [[Charles Cotton]] wrote of the \u2018Lathkin\u2019:<ref name=\"Walton2013\">{{cite book|last=Walton|first=Izaak|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=11J8CgAAQBAJ|title=The Compleat Angler|date=16 April 2013|publisher=Read Books Limited|isbn=978-1-4465-4793-9|authorlink=Izaak Walton|accessdate=18 November 2016|orig-year=1653}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|text=it is by many degrees, the purest and most transparent stream that I ever saw, either at home or abroad, and breeds, it is said, the reddest and best Trouts in England.|author=Charles Cotton|title=''[[The Compleat Angler]]''|source=}}\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Conksbury Medieval Bridge.jpg|thumb|292x292px|Conksbury medieval bridge]]\nThe medieval sheepwash bridge Conksbury Bridge now carries the road from [[Bakewell]] to [[Youlgreave]]. The nearby deserted [[Middle Ages|medieval]] settlement at Conksbury was recorded in the [[Domesday Book]] (1086 AD) as Cranchesberie. The site of earthworks and buried remains of buildings is a [[Scheduled monument|Scheduled Monument]].<ref>{{NHLE |num=1014589 |desc=Conksbury deserted medieval settlement, Over Haddon |access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref> A Vickers Wellington bomber crashed near here in 1941.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/visiting/miles-without-stiles/conksbury|title=Conksbury|last=|first=|date=|website=Peak District National Park|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nParsons Tor limestone crag is named after Reverend Robert Lomas of [[Monyash]] who fell to his death there, while riding his horse when drunk as he returned late at night from Bakewell in 1776.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.derbyshire-peakdistrict.co.uk/monyash.htm|title=Monyash - Discover Derbyshire and the Peak District|last=|first=|date=|website=Discover Derbyshire and the Peak District|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nTowards the top end of the valley Ricklow Quarry used to produce crinoidal limestone (rich in fossils 350 million years old), which looks like marble when polished and was popular with the [[Victorian era|Victorians]]. An old mill pond with a many stepped weir and a few mill stones are all that remains of Carters Mill (an old corn mill). The iron water wheel was removed from the mill for scrap during [[World War II]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe narrow stone Coal Pit Bridge at [[Youlgreave]],<ref>{{NHLE |num=1334999|desc=Coal Pit Bridge Over the River Lathkill, Youlgreave |grade=II |fewer-links=yes |access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref> the limestone footbridge at [[Over Haddon]]<ref>{{NHLE |num=1334984 |desc=Footbridge 20 Metres South of Lathkill Lodge, Over River Lathkill, Over Haddon |grade=II |fewer-links=yes |access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref> and the gritstone bridge at [[Nether Haddon]]<ref>{{NHLE |num=1109865 |desc=Bridge Over River Lathkill, Nether Haddon |grade=II |fewer-links=yes|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref> all cross the River Lathkill and are Grade II listed.\n\n=== Lead mining ===\n[[File:Bateman's House in Lathkill Dale.jpg|thumb|292x292px|Bateman's House in Lathkill Dale]]\nThe dale has a long history of [[lead mining]]. Lathkill Dale and Mandale mines and [[Sough|soughs]] are a rare and well-preserved example of mining activity dating from the 13th century onwards. They include ruins of engine houses and an [[Aqueduct (water supply)|aqueduct]] and are a Scheduled Monument. In 1797 miners started to dig the Mandale Sough into the north side of the valley. The remains of the 19th-century Mandale Mine include the ruins of a pumphouse to drain the mines (using a steam Cornish pumping engine installed in 1847). Intensive mining led to underground flooding and the closure of Lathkill Mine. However. in 1825 James Bateman, the mine agent, brought in innovative equipment to overcome the flooding. A pumping engine was installed in a shaft under the building where he lived and known since as Bateman\u2019s House. In 1836 he also erected a large and powerful waterwheel. Nevertheless, the mine became unprofitable and closed in 1842. Mandale Rake eventually closed in 1852 although individual miners continued working it until 1867.<ref name=\"NNR\" /><ref>{{NHLE ||num=1016755|desc=Lathkill Dale and Mandale mines and soughs, Over Haddon |fewer-links=yes|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Access ==\n{{short description|Valley in the Derbyshire Peak District}}\nThere are parking areas near [[Monyash]] at the top end of Lathkill Dale. There is also a car park at [[Over Haddon]] leading to a steep road that descends into the dale. Roadside parking is limited at Conksbury Bridge and at [[Alport]] at the bottom end of the dale.\n\n== References ==\n\n<references group=\"\" responsive=\"1\"></references>\n[[Category:Valleys of the Peak District]]\n[[Category:Valleys of Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Peak District]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox valley|name=Lathkill Dale|map_alt=|coordinates_ref=<!-- Statistics -->|coordinates={{Coord|53.1846|-1.7639|display=title, inline|type:river}}|label_position=|label=|relief=|location=[[Derbyshire]], [[England]]|elevation=|map_caption=|map_size=|map_image=|photo_caption=View down Lathkill Dale near Monyash|photo_alt=|photo_size=|photo=View down Lathkill Dale near Monyash.jpg|other_name=|elevation_ft=|age=|footnotes=|watercourses=[[River Lathkill]]\n<!-- Below -->|traversed=|towns=|topo=|boundaries=|type=|elevation_m=|depth=|area=|width=|length=|direction=|elevation_ref=|embed=}}\n[[File:River at Lathkill Head Cave.jpg|thumb|292x292px|Lathkill Head Cave in wet conditions]]\n{{Use dmy dates|date = March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n\n'''Lathkill Dale''' is the [[valley]] of the [[River Lathkill]] near [[Bakewell]], [[Derbyshire]] in the [[Peak District]] of England. The river emerges into the dale from springs below Lathkill Head Cave (or, in wet conditions, from the cave itself).\n\n== Nature reserve ==\nThe river valley is part of the [[Derbyshire Dales National Nature Reserve]] and is popular with tourists who visit for its natural environment and wildlife. [[Natural England]] manages the reserve which covers five separate dales of the [[White Peak]] (Lathkill Dale, Cressbrook Dale, Hay Dale, Long Dale and [[Monk\u2019s Dale]]).<ref name=\"NNR\">{{cite web|url=http://publications.naturalengland.org.uk/publication/31052?category=23001|title=Derbyshire Dales National Nature Reserve (NE154)|last=|first=|date=18 July 2014|website=|publisher=Natural England|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> The dale includes two [[Site of Special Scientific Interest|Sites of Special Scientific Interest]] (SSSIs) and areas designated as Open Access Land in the [[Countryside and Rights of Way Act 2000]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://designatedsites.naturalengland.org.uk/PDFsForWeb/Citation/1003711.pdf|title=Lathkill Dale|last=|first=|date=1972|website=|publisher=Natural England|type=SSSI citation|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://designatedsites.naturalengland.org.uk/PDFsForWeb/Citation/1003846.pdf|title=Upper Lathkill|last=|first=|date=1989|website=|publisher=Natural England|type=SSSI citation|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nLathkill Dale is known for its range of wildflower species (incuding orchids and the rare [[Polemonium caeruleum|Jacob's ladder]]), butterflies, ancient woodland and the presence of birds of prey, [[White-throated dipper|dippers]], [[Woodpecker|woodpeckers]] and [[European water vole|water voles]].\n\nThe River Lathkill is a [[Winterbourne (stream)|winterbourne stream]] (drying up in sections over summer). After heavy rain, clear river water rises up from sink-holes near [[Over Haddon]] and runs into deep pools known locally as The Blue Waters. Beyond this there are 12 weirs, which were built for trout fishing in [[Victorian era|Victorian]] times.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.peakdistrictonline.co.uk/lathkill-dale-c10113.html|title=Lathkill Dale {{!}} Peak District|last=|first=|date=|website=www.peakdistrictonline.co.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref> In 1653 the poet and angler [[Charles Cotton]] wrote of the \u2018Lathkin\u2019:<ref name=\"Walton2013\">{{cite book|last=Walton|first=Izaak|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=11J8CgAAQBAJ|title=The Compleat Angler|date=16 April 2013|publisher=Read Books Limited|isbn=978-1-4465-4793-9|authorlink=Izaak Walton|accessdate=18 November 2016|orig-year=1653}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|text=it is by many degrees, the purest and most transparent stream that I ever saw, either at home or abroad, and breeds, it is said, the reddest and best Trouts in England.|author=Charles Cotton|title=''[[The Compleat Angler]]''|source=}}\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Conksbury Medieval Bridge.jpg|thumb|292x292px|Conksbury medieval bridge]]\nThe medieval sheepwash bridge Conksbury Bridge now carries the road from [[Bakewell]] to [[Youlgreave]]. The nearby deserted [[Middle Ages|medieval]] settlement at Conksbury was recorded in the [[Domesday Book]] (1086 AD) as Cranchesberie. The site of earthworks and buried remains of buildings is a [[Scheduled monument|Scheduled Monument]].<ref>{{NHLE |num=1014589 |desc=Conksbury deserted medieval settlement, Over Haddon |access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref> A Vickers Wellington bomber crashed near here in 1941.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.peakdistrict.gov.uk/visiting/miles-without-stiles/conksbury|title=Conksbury|last=|first=|date=|website=Peak District National Park|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nParsons Tor limestone crag is named after Reverend Robert Lomas of [[Monyash]] who fell to his death there, while riding his horse when drunk as he returned late at night from Bakewell in 1776.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.derbyshire-peakdistrict.co.uk/monyash.htm|title=Monyash - Discover Derbyshire and the Peak District|last=|first=|date=|website=Discover Derbyshire and the Peak District|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nTowards the top end of the valley Ricklow Quarry used to produce crinoidal limestone (rich in fossils 350 million years old), which looks like marble when polished and was popular with the [[Victorian era|Victorians]]. An old mill pond with a many stepped weir and a few mill stones are all that remains of Carters Mill (an old corn mill). The iron water wheel was removed from the mill for scrap during [[World War II]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe narrow stone Coal Pit Bridge at [[Youlgreave]],<ref>{{NHLE |num=1334999|desc=Coal Pit Bridge Over the River Lathkill, Youlgreave |grade=II |fewer-links=yes |access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref> the limestone footbridge at [[Over Haddon]]<ref>{{NHLE |num=1334984 |desc=Footbridge 20 Metres South of Lathkill Lodge, Over River Lathkill, Over Haddon |grade=II |fewer-links=yes |access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref> and the gritstone bridge at [[Nether Haddon]]<ref>{{NHLE |num=1109865 |desc=Bridge Over River Lathkill, Nether Haddon |grade=II |fewer-links=yes|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref> all cross the River Lathkill and are Grade II listed.\n\n=== Lead mining ===\n[[File:Bateman's House in Lathkill Dale.jpg|thumb|292x292px|Bateman's House in Lathkill Dale]]\nThe dale has a long history of [[lead mining]]. Lathkill Dale and Mandale mines and [[Sough|soughs]] are a rare and well-preserved example of mining activity dating from the 13th century onwards. They include ruins of engine houses and an [[Aqueduct (water supply)|aqueduct]] and are a Scheduled Monument. In 1797 miners started to dig the Mandale Sough into the north side of the valley. The remains of the 19th-century Mandale Mine include the ruins of a pumphouse to drain the mines (using a steam Cornish pumping engine installed in 1847). Intensive mining led to underground flooding and the closure of Lathkill Mine. However. in 1825 James Bateman, the mine agent, brought in innovative equipment to overcome the flooding. A pumping engine was installed in a shaft under the building where he lived and known since as Bateman\u2019s House. In 1836 he also erected a large and powerful waterwheel. Nevertheless, the mine became unprofitable and closed in 1842. Mandale Rake eventually closed in 1852 although individual miners continued working it until 1867.<ref name=\"NNR\" /><ref>{{NHLE ||num=1016755|desc=Lathkill Dale and Mandale mines and soughs, Over Haddon |fewer-links=yes|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Access ==\n{{short description|Valley in the Derbyshire Peak District}}\nThere are parking areas near [[Monyash]] at the top end of Lathkill Dale. There is also a car park at [[Over Haddon]] leading to a steep road that descends into the dale. Roadside parking is limited at Conksbury Bridge and at [[Alport]] at the bottom end of the dale.\n\n== References ==\n\n<references group=\"\" responsive=\"1\"></references>\n[[Category:Valleys of the Peak District]]\n[[Category:Valleys of Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Peak District]]\n", "name_user": "Douglal", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed broken link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lathkill_Dale"}
{"title_page": "Trip hammer", "text_new": "[[File:St\u00e5ngj\u00e4rnshammar Gravendal video 2012.ogv|thumb|340px|thumbtime=4|Trip hammer in [[Dalarna]], [[Sweden]].]]\n[[image:Fourneau St-Michel - Martinet 2.jpg|thumb|right|240px|Trip hammer of the St. Michael's Furnace property \u2013 Museum of Iron of [[Saint-Hubert, Belgium|Saint-Hubert]] (Belgium).]]\nA '''trip hammer''', also known as a '''tilt hammer''' or '''helve hammer''', is a massive powered [[hammer]]. Traditional uses of trip hammers include pounding, [[wikt:decorticate|decorticating]] and polishing of grain in [[agriculture]]. In [[mining]], trip hammers were used for crushing metal [[ore]]s into small pieces, although a [[stamp mill]] was more usual for this. In [[finery forge]]s they were used for drawing out [[bloomery|blooms]] made from [[wrought iron]] into more workable [[Wrought iron|bar iron]]. They were also used for fabricating various articles of [[wrought iron]], [[latten]] (an early form of [[brass]]), [[steel]] and other metals.\n\nOne or more trip hammers were set up in a [[forge]], also known variously as a [[hammer mill]], hammer forge or hammer works. The hammers were usually raised by a [[cam]] and then released to fall under the force of [[Gravitation|gravity]]. Historically, trip hammers were often powered [[Hydropower|hydraulically]] by a [[water wheel]]. \n\nTrip hammers are known to have been used in [[Imperial China]] since the [[Western Han dynasty]]. They also existed in the contemporary [[Greco-Roman world]], with more evidence of their use in [[medieval Europe]] during the 12th century. During the [[Industrial Revolution]] the trip hammer fell out of favor and was replaced with the [[power hammer]]. Often multiple hammers were powered via a set of [[line shaft]]s, pulleys and belts from a centrally located power supply.\n\n==Early history==\n\n===China===\n[[File:Hydraulic-Powdered Trip Hammers.jpg|thumb|right|240px|Hydrodynamic powered trip hammer set, illustration from the ''Tiangong Kaiwu'' encyclopedia of 1637, written by [[Song Yingxing]] (1587\u20131666)]]\nIn ancient China, the trip hammer evolved out of the use of the [[mortar and pestle]], which in turn gave rise to the treadle-operated tilt-hammer ([[Chinese language|Chinese]]: \u7893 [[Pinyin]]: ''dui''; [[Wade-Giles]]: ''tui'').<ref name=\"neehdam volume 4 part 2 183\" >Needham, Volume 4, Part 2, 183.</ref> The latter was a simple device employing a lever and fulcrum (operated by pressure applied by the weight of one's foot to one end), which featured a series of catches or lugs on the main revolving shaft as well.<ref name=\"needham volume 4 part 2 390\">Needham, Volume 4, Part 2, 390.</ref> This device enabled the labor of pounding, often in the decorticating and polishing of grain, and avoided manual use of pounding with hand and arm. Although historians assert that its origins may span as far back as the [[Zhou Dynasty]] (1050 BC\u2013221 BC), the earliest texts to describe the device are the ''[[Jijiupian]]'' dictionary of 40 BC, [[Yang Xiong (author)|Yang Xiong]]'s text known as the ''[[Fangyan]]'' of 15 BC, as well as the ''Xin Lun'' written by [[Huan Tan]] about 20 AD (during the usurpation of [[Wang Mang]]).<ref name=\"needham volume 4 part 2 184\" >Needham, Volume 4, Part 2, 184.</ref> The latter book states that the legendary mythological king known as [[Fu Xi]] was the one responsible for the pestle and mortar (which evolved into the tilt-hammer and then trip hammer device). Although the author speaks of the mythological Fu Xi, a passage of his writing gives hint that the waterwheel and trip-hammer were in widespread use by the 1st century AD in China (for water-powered Chinese [[metallurgy]], see [[Du Shi]]):\n\n<blockquote>Fu Hsi invented the pestle and mortar, which is so useful, and later on it was cleverly improved in such a way that the whole weight of the body could be used for treading on the tilt-hammer (tui), thus increasing the efficiency ten times. Afterwards the power of animals\u2014donkeys, mules, oxen, and horses\u2014was applied by means of machinery, and water-power too used for pounding, so that the benefit was increased a hundredfold.<ref name=\"needham volume 4 part 2 392\">Needham, Volume 4, Part 2, 392.</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nWith his description, it is seen that the out-of-date Chinese term for pestle and mortar (dui, tui) would soon be replaced with the Chinese term for the water-powered trip-hammer ({{zh|links=no|c=\u6c34\u7893|p=shu\u01d0 du\u00ec|w=shui tui}}.<ref name=\"needham volume 4 part 2 390\"/> The [[Han Dynasty]] scholar and poet [[Ma Rong]] (79\u2013166 AD) mentioned in one of his poems of hammers 'pounding in the water-echoing caves'.<ref name=\"needham volume 4 part 2 392\"/> As described in the ''[[Hou Han Shu]]'', in 129 AD the official [[Yu Xu (official)|Yu Xu]] gave a report to [[Emperor Shun of Han]] that trip hammers were being exported from Han China to the Western [[Qiang people]] by way of canals through the [[Qilian Mountains]].<ref name=\"needham volume 4 part 2 392\"/> In his ''Rou Xing Lun'', the government official [[Kong Rong]] (153\u2013208 AD) remarked that the invention of the trip hammer was an excellent example of a product created by intelligent men during his own age (comparing the relative achievements of the sages of old).<ref name=\"needham volume 4 part 2 392\"/> During the 3rd century AD, the high government official and engineer [[Du Yu]] established the use of combined trip hammer batteries (lian zhi dui), which employed several shafts that were arranged to work off one large waterwheel.<ref name=\"needham volume 4 part 2 393\">Needham, Volume 4, Part 2, 393.</ref> In Chinese texts of the 4th century, there are written accounts of men possessing and operating hundreds of trip hammer machines, such as the venerable mathematician Wang Rong (died 306 AD), Deng Yu (died 326 AD), and Shi Chong (died 300 AD), responsible for the operation of hundreds of trip hammers in over thirty governmental districts throughout China.<ref name=\"needham volume 4 part 2 392-393\">Needham, Volume 4, Part 2, 392-393.</ref> There are numerous references to trip hammers during the [[Tang Dynasty]] (618\u2013907 AD) and [[Song Dynasty]] (960\u20131279), and there are [[Ming Dynasty]] (1368\u20131644) references that report the use of trip hammers in [[papermill]]s of [[Fujian]] Province.<ref name=\"needham volume 4 part 2 394\">Needham, Volume 4, Part 2, 394.</ref>\n\nAlthough Chinese trip hammers in China were sometimes powered by the more efficient vertical-set waterwheel, the Chinese often employed the horizontal-set waterwheel in operating trip hammers, along with recumbent hammers.<ref name=\"needham volume 4 part 2 391 392\">Needham, Volume 4, Part 2, 391\u2013392.</ref> The recumbent hammer was found in Chinese illustrations by 1313 AD, with the publishing of [[Wang Zhen (official)|Wang Zhen]]'s ''Nong Shu'' book on ancient and contemporary (medieval) metallurgy in China.<ref name=\"needham volume 4 part 2 395\">Needham, Volume 4, Part 2, 395.</ref> There were also illustrations of trip hammers in an encyclopedia of 1637, written by [[Song Yingxing]] (1587\u20131666).<ref name=\"Song 91 93\">Song, 91\u201393.</ref>\n\n=== Greco-Roman world ===\n[[File:Carreg Pumsaint - geograph.org.uk - 396874.jpg|thumb|The regular indentations on the [[Dolaucothi Gold Mines#Carreg Pumsaint|Carreg Pumsaint]] and similar mortar blocks are believed to stem from mechanically-operated trip hammers.<ref name=\"Barry C. Burnham, p.333-335\"/>]]\n\nThe main components for water-powered trip hammers \u2013 [[water wheel]]s, [[cam]]s, and hammers \u2013 were already known in [[Hellenistic civilization|Hellenistic times]].<ref>Andrew Wilson: \u201cMachines, Power and the Ancient Economy\u201d, ''The Journal of Roman Studies'', Vol. 92. (2002), pp. 1-32 (22)</ref> [[Antiquity|Ancient]] cams are in evidence in early water-powered [[Automaton|automata]] from the third century BC.<ref name=\"Andrew Wilson, p.16\"/> A passage in the ''[[Natural History]]'' of the [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] scholar [[Pliny the Elder|Pliny]] (NH 18.97) indicates that water-driven pestles had become fairly widespread in [[Italy]] by the first century AD.<ref name=\"Andrew Wilson, p.16\">Andrew Wilson: \u201cMachines, Power and the Ancient Economy\u201d, ''The Journal of Roman Studies'', Vol. 92. (2002), pp. 1-32 (16)</ref> These trip-hammers were used for the pounding and hulling of [[grain]].<ref name=\"Andrew Wilson, p.16\"/> Grain-pounders with pestles, as well as ordinary [[watermill]]s, are also attested as late as the middle of the fifth century in a [[monastery]] founded by [[Romanus of Condat]] in the remote [[Jura]] region, indicating that the knowledge of trip hammers continued into the early [[Middle Ages]].<ref name=\"Andrew Wilson, p.16\"/>\n\nThe widest application of trip hammers seems to have occurred in Roman mining, where [[ore]] from deep veins was first crushed into small pieces for further processing.<ref name=\"Andrew Wilson, p.21f.\"/> Here, the regularity and spacing of large indentations on stone [[anvil]]s indicate the use of cam-operated ore stamps, much like the devices of later [[Middle Ages|medieval]] mining.<ref name=\"Andrew Wilson, p.21f.\"/><ref name=\"Barry C. Burnham, p.333-335\">Barry C. Burnham: \"Roman Mining at Dolaucothi: The Implications of the 1991-3 Excavations near the Carreg Pumsaint\", ''Britannia'', Vol. 28 (1997), pp. 325-336 (333-335)</ref> Such mechanically deformed anvils have been found at numerous Roman silver and gold mining sites in [[Western Europe]], including at [[Dolaucothi]] ([[Wales]]), and on the [[Iberian peninsula]],<ref name=\"Andrew Wilson, p.21f.\"/><ref name=\"Barry C. Burnham, p.333-335\"/><ref>J. Wahl: \"Tres Minas: Vorbericht \u00fcber die arch\u00e4ologischen Ausgrabungen im Bereich des r\u00f6mischen Goldbergwerks 1986/87\", in H. Steuer and U. Zimmerman (eds): \"Montanarch\u00e4ologie in Europa\", 1993, p.123-152 (141; Fig.19)</ref> where the datable examples are from the 1st and 2nd century AD.<ref>Andrew Wilson: \u201cMachines, Power and the Ancient Economy\u201d, ''The Journal of Roman Studies'', Vol. 92. (2002), pp. 1-32 (21, Fn.110)</ref> At Dolaucothi, these trip-hammers were hydraulic-driven and possibly also at other Roman mining sites, where the large scale use of the [[Hushing|hushing and ground sluicing technique]] meant that large amounts of water were directly available for powering the machines.<ref name=\"Andrew Wilson, p.21f.\">Andrew Wilson: \u201cMachines, Power and the Ancient Economy\u201d, ''The Journal of Roman Studies'', Vol. 92. (2002), pp. 1-32 (21f.)</ref><ref>M.J.T. Lewis: \"Millstone and Hammer: the Origins of Water Power\", (1997), Section 2</ref>\n\n=== Medieval Europe ===\n[[File:Agricola Stamp ore crusher.png|thumb|Water-powered ore crusher by [[Georgius Agricola]]]]\n\nWater-powered and mechanised trip hammers reappeared in [[Middle Ages|medieval Europe]] by the 12th century. Their use was described in medieval written sources of [[Styria]] (in modern-day Austria), written in 1135 and another in 1175 AD.<ref name=\"needham volume 4 part 2 379\" >Needham, Volume 4, Part 2, 379.</ref> Medieval French sources of the years 1116 and 1249 both record the use of mechanised trip hammers used in the forging of [[wrought iron]].<ref name=\"needham volume 4 part 2 379\"/> Medieval European trip hammers by the 15th century were most often in the shape of the vertical pestle stamp-mill, although they employed more frequent use of the vertical waterwheel than earlier Chinese versions (which often used the horizontal waterwheel).<ref name=\"needham volume 4 part 2 394\" /> The well-known [[Renaissance]] artist and inventor [[Leonardo da Vinci]] often sketched trip hammers for use in forges and even file-cutting machinery, those of the vertical pestle stamp-mill type.<ref name=\"needham volume 4 part 2 395\"/> The oldest depicted European illustration of a [[martinet]] forge-hammer is perhaps the [[Historia de Gentibus Septentrionalibus]] of [[Olaus Magnus]], dated to 1565 AD.<ref name=\"needham volume 4 part 2 395\"/> In this woodcut image, there is the scene of three martinets and a waterwheel working wood and leather bellows of the [[Osmund Bloomery]] furnace.<ref name=\"needham volume 4 part 2 395\"/> The recumbent hammer was first depicted in European artwork in an illustration by [[Joachim von Sandrart|Sandrart]] and [[Zonca]] (dated 1621 AD).<ref name=\"needham volume 4 part 2 395\"/>\n\n==Types==\nA trip hammer has the head mounted at the end of a recumbent [[wikt:helve#Noun|helve]], hence the alternative name of helve hammer.  The choice of which type was used in a particular context may have depended on the strain that its operation imposed on the helve.  This was normally of wood, mounted in a cast iron ring (called the hurst) where it pivoted.  However, in the 19th century the heaviest helves were sometimes a single casting, incorporating the hurst.\n\n[[File:Abbeydale Industrial Hamlet - Tilt Hammers - geograph.org.uk - 2425530.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Water-powered hammers at Abbeydale Industrial Hamlet]]\nThe '''tilt hammer''' or '''tail helve hammer''' has a pivot at the centre of the helve on which it is mounted, and is lifted by pushing the opposite end to the head downwards. In practice, the head on such hammers seems to have been limited <!-- in England? -->to one hundredweight (about 50&nbsp;kg), but a very rapid stroke rate was possible. This made it suitable for drawing iron down to small sizes suitable for the cutlery trades.  There were therefore many such forges known as 'tilts' around [[Sheffield]]. They were also used in [[brass]] battery works for making brass (or copper) pots and pans. In battery works (at least) it was possible for one power source to operate several hammers. In Germany, tilt hammers of up to 300&nbsp;kg were used in hammer mills to forge iron. Surviving, working hammers, powered by water wheels, may be seen, for example, at the [[Frohnauer Hammer]] in the [[Ore Mountains]].\n\nThe '''belly helve hammer''' was the kind normally found in a [[finery forge]], used for making [[pig iron]] into forgeable bar iron. This was lifted by cams striking the helve between the pivot and the head. The head usually weighed quarter of a ton. This was probably the case because the strain on a wooden helve would have been too great if the head were heavier.\n\nThe '''nose helve hammer''' seems to have been unusual until the late 18th or early 19th century. This was lifted beyond the head.  Surviving nose helves<ref>For example at [[Abbeydale Industrial Hamlet]]{{dubious|see picture}}</ref> and those in pictures<ref>For example in the metalwork gallery in [[Birmingham Museum & Art Gallery]]</ref> appear to be of cast iron.\n\n=== Demise ===\nThe steam-powered [[drop hammer]] replaced the trip hammer (at least for the largest forgings).  [[James Hall Nasmyth|James Nasmyth]] invented it in 1839 and [[patent]]ed in 1842.  However, by then forging had become less important for the iron industry, following the improvements to the [[rolling mill]] that went along with the adoption of [[puddling (metallurgy)|puddling]] from the end of the 18th century.  Nevertheless, hammers continued to be needed for [[shingling]].\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Abbeydale Industrial Hamlet]]\n*[[Dorfchemnitz Iron Hammer Mill]]\n*[[Finch Foundry]]\n*[[Freibergsdorf Hammer Mill]]\n*[[Frohnauer Hammer Mill]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|33em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*Sim, David and Ridge, Isable: \"Iron for the Eagles\" (2002)\n*Burnham, Barry C.: \"Dolaucothi-Pumsaint: Survey and Excavations at a Roman Gold-mining Complex\" (2004)\n*Lewis, M.J.T.: \"Millstone and Hammer: the Origins of Water Power\" (1997)\n*Needham, Joseph; Wang, Ling. (1986) [1965]. ''Science and Civilization in China: Volume 4, Physics and Physical Technology, Part 2, Mechanical Engineering''. Taipei: Caves Books Ltd (reprint edition of Cambridge & New York: Cambridge University Press). {{ISBN|0-521-05803-1}}.\n*Song, Yingxing, translated with preface by E-Tu Zen Sun and Shiou-Chuan Sun: ''T'ien-Kung K'ai-Wu: Chinese Technology in the Seventeenth Century''. (University Park: Pennsylvania State University Press 1966).\n*[[Andrew Wilson (classical archaeologist)|Wilson, Andrew]] (2002): \"Machines, Power and the Ancient Economy\", ''[[The Journal of Roman Studies]]'', Vol. 92, pp.&nbsp;1\u201332 (16, 21f.)\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Trip hammers}}\n*{{cite web|title=Diagram of a forge trip hammer|url=http://explorepahistory.com/displayimage.php?imgId=1-2-E52|work=ExplorePAHistory.com|publisher=WITF; Pennsylvania Historical and Museum Commission|accessdate=22 January 2013}}\n\n{{Metalworking navbox|smithopen}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trip Hammer}}\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Chinese inventions]]\n[[Category:Hammers]]\n[[Category:Metalworking tools]]\n[[Category:Power hammers]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:St\u00e5ngj\u00e4rnshammar Gravendal video 2012.ogv|thumb|340px|thumbtime=4|Trip hammer in [[Dalarna]], [[Sweden]].]]\n[[image:Fourneau St-Michel - Martinet 2.jpg|thumb|right|240px|Trip hammer of the St. Michael's Furnace property \u2013 Museum of Iron of [[Saint-Hubert, Belgium|Saint-Hubert]] (Belgium).]]\nA '''trip hammer''', also known as a '''tilt hammer''' or '''helve hammer''', is a massive powered [[hammer]]. Traditional uses of trip hammers include pounding, [[wikt:decorticate|decorticating]] and polishing of grain in [[agriculture]]. In [[mining]], trip hammers were used for crushing metal [[ore]]s into small pieces, although a [[stamp mill]] was more usual for this. In [[finery forge]]s they were used for drawing out [[bloomery|blooms]] made from [[wrought iron]] into more workable [[Wrought iron|bar iron]]. They were also used for fabricating various articles of [[wrought iron]], [[latten]] (an early form of [[brass]]), [[steel]] and other metals.\n\nOne or more trip hammers were set up in a [[forge]], also known variously as a [[hammer mill]], hammer forge or hammer works. The hammers were usually raised by a [[cam]] and then released to fall under the force of [[Gravitation|gravity]]. Historically, trip hammers were often powered [[Hydropower|hydraulically]] by a [[water wheel]]. \n\nTrip hammers are known to have been used in [[Imperial China]] since the [[Western Han dynasty]]. They also existed in the contemporary [[Greco-Roman world]], with more evidence of their use in [[medieval Europe]] during the 12th century. During the [[Industrial Revolution]] the trip hammer fell out of favor and was replaced with the [[power hammer]]. Often multiple hammers were powered via a set of [[line shaft]]s, pulleys and belts from a centrally located power supply.\n\n==Early history==\n\n===China===\n[[File:Hydraulic-Powdered Trip Hammers.jpg|thumb|right|240px|Hydrodynamic powered trip hammer set, illustration from the ''Tiangong Kaiwu'' encyclopedia of 1637, written by [[Song Yingxing]] (1587\u20131666)]]\nIn ancient China, the trip hammer evolved out of the use of the [[mortar and pestle]], which in turn gave rise to the treadle-operated tilt-hammer ([[Chinese language|Chinese]]: \u7893 [[Pinyin]]: ''dui''; [[Wade-Giles]]: ''tui'').<ref name=\"neehdam volume 4 part 2 183\" >Needham, Volume 4, Part 2, 183.</ref> The latter was a simple device employing a lever and fulcrum (operated by pressure applied by the weight of one's foot to one end), which featured a series of catches or lugs on the main revolving shaft as well.<ref name=\"needham volume 4 part 2 390\">Needham, Volume 4, Part 2, 390.</ref> This device enabled the labor of pounding, often in the decorticating and polishing of grain, and avoided manual use of pounding with hand and arm. Although historians assert that its origins may span as far back as the [[Zhou Dynasty]] (1050 BC\u2013221 BC), the earliest texts to describe the device are the ''[[Jijiupian]]'' dictionary of 40 BC, [[Yang Xiong (author)|Yang Xiong]]'s text known as the ''[[Fangyan]]'' of 15 BC, as well as the ''Xin Lun'' written by [[Huan Tan]] about 20 AD (during the usurpation of [[Wang Mang]]).<ref name=\"needham volume 4 part 2 184\" >Needham, Volume 4, Part 2, 184.</ref> The latter book states that the legendary mythological king known as [[Fu Xi]] was the one responsible for the pestle and mortar (which evolved into the tilt-hammer and then trip hammer device). Although the author speaks of the mythological Fu Xi, a passage of his writing gives hint that the waterwheel and trip-hammer were in widespread use by the 1st century AD in China (for water-powered Chinese [[metallurgy]], see [[Du Shi]]):\n\n<blockquote>Fu Hsi invented the pestle and mortar, which is so useful, and later on it was cleverly improved in such a way that the whole weight of the body could be used for treading on the tilt-hammer (tui), thus increasing the efficiency ten times. Afterwards the power of animals\u2014donkeys, mules, oxen, and horses\u2014was applied by means of machinery, and water-power too used for pounding, so that the benefit was increased a hundredfold.<ref name=\"needham volume 4 part 2 392\">Needham, Volume 4, Part 2, 392.</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nWith his description, it is seen that the out-of-date Chinese term for pestle and mortar (dui, tui) would soon be replaced with the Chinese term for the water-powered trip-hammer ({{zh|links=no|c=\u6c34\u7893|p=shu\u01d0 du\u00ec|w=shui tui}}.<ref name=\"needham volume 4 part 2 390\"/> The [[Han Dynasty]] scholar and poet [[Ma Rong]] (79\u2013166 AD) mentioned in one of his poems of hammers 'pounding in the water-echoing caves'.<ref name=\"needham volume 4 part 2 392\"/> As described in the ''[[Hou Han Shu]]'', in 129 AD the official [[Yu Xu (official)|Yu Xu]] gave a report to [[Emperor Shun of Han]] that trip hammers were being exported from Han China to the Western [[Qiang people]] by way of canals through the [[Qilian Mountains]].<ref name=\"needham volume 4 part 2 392\"/> In his ''Rou Xing Lun'', the government official [[Kong Rong]] (153\u2013208 AD) remarked that the invention of the trip hammer was an excellent example of a product created by intelligent men during his own age (comparing the relative achievements of the sages of old).<ref name=\"needham volume 4 part 2 392\"/> During the 3rd century AD, the high government official and engineer [[Du Yu]] established the use of combined trip hammer batteries (lian zhi dui), which employed several shafts that were arranged to work off one large waterwheel.<ref name=\"needham volume 4 part 2 393\">Needham, Volume 4, Part 2, 393.</ref> In Chinese texts of the 4th century, there are written accounts of men possessing and operating hundreds of trip hammer machines, such as the venerable mathematician Wang Rong (died 306 AD), Deng Yu (died 326 AD), and Shi Chong (died 300 AD), responsible for the operation of hundreds of trip hammers in over thirty governmental districts throughout China.<ref name=\"needham volume 4 part 2 392-393\">Needham, Volume 4, Part 2, 392-393.</ref> There are numerous references to trip hammers during the [[Tang Dynasty]] (618\u2013907 AD) and [[Song Dynasty]] (960\u20131279), and there are [[Ming Dynasty]] (1368\u20131644) references that report the use of trip hammers in [[papermill]]s of [[Fujian]] Province.<ref name=\"needham volume 4 part 2 394\">Needham, Volume 4, Part 2, 394.</ref>\n\nAlthough Chinese trip hammers in China were sometimes powered by the more efficient vertical-set waterwheel, the Chinese often employed the horizontal-set waterwheel in operating trip hammers, along with recumbent hammers.<ref name=\"needham volume 4 part 2 391 392\">Needham, Volume 4, Part 2, 391\u2013392.</ref> The recumbent hammer was found in Chinese illustrations by 1313 AD, with the publishing of [[Wang Zhen (official)|Wang Zhen]]'s ''Nong Shu'' book on ancient and contemporary (medieval) metallurgy in China.<ref name=\"needham volume 4 part 2 395\">Needham, Volume 4, Part 2, 395.</ref> There were also illustrations of trip hammers in an encyclopedia of 1637, written by [[Song Yingxing]] (1587\u20131666).<ref name=\"Song 91 93\">Song, 91\u201393.</ref>\n\n=== Greco-Roman world ===\n[[File:Carreg Pumsaint - geograph.org.uk - 396874.jpg|thumb|The regular indentations on the [[Dolaucothi Gold Mines#Carreg Pumsaint|Carreg Pumsaint]] and similar mortar blocks are believed to stem from mechanically-operated trip hammers.<ref name=\"Barry C. Burnham, p.333-335\"/>]]\n\nThe main components for water-powered trip hammers \u2013 [[water wheel]]s, [[cam]]s, and hammers \u2013 were already known in [[Hellenistic civilization|Hellenistic times]].<ref>Andrew Wilson: \u201cMachines, Power and the Ancient Economy\u201d, ''The Journal of Roman Studies'', Vol. 92. (2002), pp. 1-32 (22)</ref> [[Antiquity|Ancient]] cams are in evidence in early water-powered [[Automaton|automata]] from the third century BC.<ref name=\"Andrew Wilson, p.16\"/> A passage in the ''[[Natural History]]'' of the [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] scholar [[Pliny the Elder|Pliny]] (NH 18.97) indicates that water-driven pestles had become fairly widespread in [[Italy]] by the first century AD.<ref name=\"Andrew Wilson, p.16\">Andrew Wilson: \u201cMachines, Power and the Ancient Economy\u201d, ''The Journal of Roman Studies'', Vol. 92. (2002), pp. 1-32 (16)</ref> These trip-hammers were used for the pounding and hulling of [[grain]].<ref name=\"Andrew Wilson, p.16\"/> Grain-pounders with pestles, as well as ordinary [[watermill]]s, are also attested as late as the middle of the fifth century in a [[monastery]] founded by [[Romanus of Condat]] in the remote [[Jura]] region, indicating that the knowledge of trip hammers continued into the early [[Middle Ages]].<ref name=\"Andrew Wilson, p.16\"/>\n\nThe widest application of trip hammers seems to have occurred in Roman mining, where [[ore]] from deep veins was first crushed into small pieces for further processing.<ref name=\"Andrew Wilson, p.21f.\"/> Here, the regularity and spacing of large indentations on stone [[anvil]]s indicate the use of cam-operated ore stamps, much like the devices of later [[Middle Ages|medieval]] mining.<ref name=\"Andrew Wilson, p.21f.\"/><ref name=\"Barry C. Burnham, p.333-335\">Barry C. Burnham: \"Roman Mining at Dolaucothi: The Implications of the 1991-3 Excavations near the Carreg Pumsaint\", ''Britannia'', Vol. 28 (1997), pp. 325-336 (333-335)</ref> Such mechanically deformed anvils have been found at numerous Roman silver and gold mining sites in [[Western Europe]], including at [[Dolaucothi]] ([[Wales]]), and on the [[Iberian peninsula]],<ref name=\"Andrew Wilson, p.21f.\"/><ref name=\"Barry C. Burnham, p.333-335\"/><ref>J. Wahl: \"Tres Minas: Vorbericht \u00fcber die arch\u00e4ologischen Ausgrabungen im Bereich des r\u00f6mischen Goldbergwerks 1986/87\", in H. Steuer and U. Zimmerman (eds): \"Montanarch\u00e4ologie in Europa\", 1993, p.123-152 (141; Fig.19)</ref> where the datable examples are from the 1st and 2nd century AD.<ref>Andrew Wilson: \u201cMachines, Power and the Ancient Economy\u201d, ''The Journal of Roman Studies'', Vol. 92. (2002), pp. 1-32 (21, Fn.110)</ref> At Dolaucothi, these trip-hammers were hydraulic-driven and possibly also at other Roman mining sites, where the large scale use of the [[Hushing|hushing and ground sluicing technique]] meant that large amounts of water were directly available for powering the machines.<ref name=\"Andrew Wilson, p.21f.\">Andrew Wilson: \u201cMachines, Power and the Ancient Economy\u201d, ''The Journal of Roman Studies'', Vol. 92. (2002), pp. 1-32 (21f.)</ref><ref>M.J.T. Lewis: \"Millstone and Hammer: the Origins of Water Power\", (1997), Section 2</ref>\n\n=== Medieval Europe ===\n[[File:Agricola Stamp ore crusher.png|thumb|Water-powered ore crusher by [[Georgius Agricola]]]]\n\nWater-powered and mechanised trip hammers reappeared in [[Middle Ages|medieval Europe]] by the 12th century. Their use was described in medieval written sources of [[Styria]] (in modern-day Austria), written in 1135 and another in 1175 AD.<ref name=\"needham volume 4 part 2 379\" >Needham, Volume 4, Part 2, 379.</ref> Medieval French sources of the years 1116 and 1249 both record the use of mechanised trip hammers used in the forging of [[wrought iron]].<ref name=\"needham volume 4 part 2 379\"/> Medieval European trip hammers by the 15th century were most often in the shape of the vertical pestle stamp-mill, although they employed more frequent use of the vertical waterwheel than earlier Chinese versions (which often used the horizontal waterwheel).<ref name=\"needham volume 4 part 2 394\" /> The well-known [[Renaissance]] artist and inventor [[Leonardo da Vinci]] often sketched trip hammers for use in forges and even file-cutting machinery, those of the vertical pestle stamp-mill type.<ref name=\"needham volume 4 part 2 395\"/> The oldest depicted European illustration of a [[martinet]] forge-hammer is perhaps the [[Historia de Gentibus Septentrionalibus]] of [[Olaus Magnus]], dated to 1565 AD.<ref name=\"needham volume 4 part 2 395\"/> In this woodcut image, there is the scene of three martinets and a waterwheel working wood and leather bellows of the [[Osmund Bloomery]] furnace.<ref name=\"needham volume 4 part 2 395\"/> The recumbent hammer was first depicted in European artwork in an illustration by [[Joachim von Sandrart|Sandrart]] and [[Zonca]] (dated 1621 AD).<ref name=\"needham volume 4 part 2 395\"/>\n\n==Types==\nA trip hammer has the head mounted at the end of a recumbent [[wikt:helve#Noun|helve]], hence the alternative name of helve hammer.  The choice of which type was used in a particular context may have depended on the strain that its operation imposed on the helve.  This was normally of wood, mounted in a cast iron ring (called the hurst) where it pivoted.  However, in the 19th century the heaviest helves were sometimes a single casting, incorporating the hurst.\n\n[[File:Abbeydale Industrial Hamlet - Tilt Hammers - geograph.org.uk - 2425530.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Water-powered hammers at Abbeydale Industrial Hamlet]]\nThe '''tilt hammer''' or '''tail helve hammer''' has a pivot at the centre of the helve on which it is mounted, and is lifted by pushing the opposite end to the head downwards. In practice, the head on such hammers seems to have been limited <!-- in England? -->to one hundredweight (about 50&nbsp;kg), but a very rapid stroke rate was possible. This made it suitable for drawing iron down to small sizes suitable for the cutlery trades.  There were therefore many such forges known as 'tilts' around [[Sheffield]]. They were also used in [[brass]] battery works for making brass (or copper) pots and pans. In battery works (at least) it was possible for one power source to operate several hammers. In Germany, tilt hammers of up to 300&nbsp;kg were used in hammer mills to forge iron. Surviving, working hammers, powered by water wheels, may be seen, for example, at the [[Frohnauer Hammer]] in the [[Ore Mountains]].\n\nThe '''belly helve hammer''' was the kind normally found in a [[finery forge]], used for making [[pig iron]] into forgeable bar iron. This was lifted by cams striking the helve between the pivot and the head. The head usually weighed quarter of a ton. This was probably the case because the strain on a wooden helve would have been too great if the head were heavier.\n\nThe '''nose helve hammer''' seems to have been unusual until the late 18th or early 19th century. This was lifted beyond the head.  Surviving nose helves<ref>For example at [[Abbeydale Industrial Hamlet]]</ref> and those in pictures<ref>For example in the metalwork gallery in [[Birmingham Museum & Art Gallery]]</ref> appear to be of cast iron.\n\n=== Demise ===\nThe steam-powered [[drop hammer]] replaced the trip hammer (at least for the largest forgings).  [[James Hall Nasmyth|James Nasmyth]] invented it in 1839 and [[patent]]ed in 1842.  However, by then forging had become less important for the iron industry, following the improvements to the [[rolling mill]] that went along with the adoption of [[puddling (metallurgy)|puddling]] from the end of the 18th century.  Nevertheless, hammers continued to be needed for [[shingling]].\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Abbeydale Industrial Hamlet]]\n*[[Dorfchemnitz Iron Hammer Mill]]\n*[[Finch Foundry]]\n*[[Freibergsdorf Hammer Mill]]\n*[[Frohnauer Hammer Mill]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|33em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*Sim, David and Ridge, Isable: \"Iron for the Eagles\" (2002)\n*Burnham, Barry C.: \"Dolaucothi-Pumsaint: Survey and Excavations at a Roman Gold-mining Complex\" (2004)\n*Lewis, M.J.T.: \"Millstone and Hammer: the Origins of Water Power\" (1997)\n*Needham, Joseph; Wang, Ling. (1986) [1965]. ''Science and Civilization in China: Volume 4, Physics and Physical Technology, Part 2, Mechanical Engineering''. Taipei: Caves Books Ltd (reprint edition of Cambridge & New York: Cambridge University Press). {{ISBN|0-521-05803-1}}.\n*Song, Yingxing, translated with preface by E-Tu Zen Sun and Shiou-Chuan Sun: ''T'ien-Kung K'ai-Wu: Chinese Technology in the Seventeenth Century''. (University Park: Pennsylvania State University Press 1966).\n*[[Andrew Wilson (classical archaeologist)|Wilson, Andrew]] (2002): \"Machines, Power and the Ancient Economy\", ''[[The Journal of Roman Studies]]'', Vol. 92, pp.&nbsp;1\u201332 (16, 21f.)\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Trip hammers}}\n*{{cite web|title=Diagram of a forge trip hammer|url=http://explorepahistory.com/displayimage.php?imgId=1-2-E52|work=ExplorePAHistory.com|publisher=WITF; Pennsylvania Historical and Museum Commission|accessdate=22 January 2013}}\n\n{{Metalworking navbox|smithopen}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trip Hammer}}\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Chinese inventions]]\n[[Category:Hammers]