{"title_page": ".277 Wolverine", "text_new": "{{Infobox firearm cartridge \n|name=.277 Wolverine\n|image=\n|caption=\n|type=Rifle\n|origin= [[United States]]\n|designer=Mark Kexel, Mad Dog Weapon Systems, Inc.\n|design_date=2014\n|parent=[[5.56\u00d745mm NATO]]\n|case_type=Rimless, Bottleneck\n|bullet=0.277&nbsp;in (7.04&nbsp;[[Millimetre|mm]])\n|neck=0.3089&nbsp;in (7.85&nbsp;mm)\n|shoulder=0.356&nbsp;in (9.04&nbsp;mm)\n|base=0.377&nbsp;in (9.58&nbsp;mm)\n|rim_dia=0.378&nbsp;in (9.60&nbsp;mm)\n|rim_thick=\n|case_length=1.530-1.535&nbsp;in (38.86&nbsp;mm, trim) to 1.545&nbsp;in (39.24&nbsp;mm, max.)\n|length=2.26&nbsp;in (57.40&nbsp;mm) max. COAL (typical)\n|rifling=1:7 (subsonic/supersonic), 1:11 (supersonic)\n|primer=Small rifle\n<!-- Ballistic performance -->\n|is_SI_ballistics=\n|bw1=85\n|btype1=\n|vel1=2800\n|en1=1480\n|bw2=90\n|btype2=\n|vel2=2750\n|en2=1510\n|bw3=95\n|btype3=\n|vel3=2650\n|en3=1480\n|bw4=100\n|btype4=\n|vel4=2600\n|en4=1500\n|bw5=110\n|btype5=\n|vel5=2500\n|en5=1525\n|test_barrel_length=16 in\n|balsrc= <ref name=\"MDWS-home\">{{cite web|url=http://www.maddogweapons.com/277-wolverine.html |title=277 Wolverine - Mad Dog Weapon Systems |publisher=Maddogweapons.com |date= |accessdate=2015-06-17}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''.277 Wolverine''' (6.8\u00d739mm) is a [[wildcat cartridge]]. It is a multi-purpose mid-power [[Cartridge (firearms)|cartridge]] with increased [[Ballistics|ballistic]] performance over the [[AR-15]]'s traditional [[.223 Remington]] ([[5.56\u00d745mm NATO]]) cartridge requiring only a new [[Gun barrel|barrel]] to upgrade/convert any 5.56-based firearm to .277 Wolverine.<ref name=\"WPI-blog\">{{cite web|last1=Hull|first1=John|title=The .277 Wolverine: Birth of a Wildcat|url=http://blog.westernpowders.com/2014/12/the-277-wolverine-birth-of-a-wildcat|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150312194421/http://blog.westernpowders.com/2014/12/the-277-wolverine-birth-of-a-wildcat/|url-status=dead|archive-date=2015-03-12|website=WesternPowders.com|publisher=Western Powders, Inc|accessdate=2015-12-31}}</ref>\n\n==Design==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=March 2019}}\nFor fundamentally the same reasons that a .277 inch (7.04&nbsp;mm) diameter [[bullet]] was selected for the [[6.8mm Remington SPC]] (i.e., ideal mass-to-diameter-to-length for mid-weight bullets constrained to loading in an AR-15/M16 [[STANAG magazine]]), selected 6.8mm as the basis for a new [[ArmaLite AR-15|AR-15]] wildcat. Like the [[.300 AAC Blackout]] and unlike the 6.8 SPC and other \"larger bore\" AR-15 cartridges, the .277 Wolverine is based on the widely available 5.56\u00d745mm parent case. Therefore, rifle components such as the [[Bolt (firearms)|bolt]] and [[Magazine (firearms)|magazine]] are interchangeable between 5.56\u00d745mm and .277 Wolverine firearms, and standard AR-15 magazines can be used with no loss of capacity. A new barrel is the minimum required component to convert a standard AR-15 to .277 Wolverine.\n\nIn order to load heavier (therefore longer) bullets to magazine length without the problems of seating the bullet's ogive into the case mouth, the Wolverine case is shortened to approximately 39&nbsp;mm from its 45&nbsp;mm parent brass. The case is resized and formed in a single-step operation to create new 23-[[Degree (angle)|degree]] shoulder and larger neck.\n\nInitial design focused on optimal performance with [[supersonic]] bullets in the 85-115&nbsp;[[Grain (unit)|gr]] (5.5-7.5&nbsp;[[Gram|g]]) class, therefore a 1:11 twist rate barrel with 5R rifling was selected.  Subsequent consumer interest in firing \"heavy-for-caliber\" [[speed of sound|subsonic]] bullets led to the design, testing, and production of 1:7 twist barrels to stabilize the longer heavier bullets.\n\n==Development==\nInitially developed, tested, and marketed as a proprietary cartridge, MDWS publicly released the detailed chamber and headspace gage specifications/drawings for the .277 Wolverine in June 2015.\n\nAt least four commercial manufacturers have produced .277 Wolverine barrels, mostly for AR-15 conversions \u2013 although MDWS also sells barrels for Savage and Remington bolt-action rifles.  Barrel manufacturers include: X-Caliber, McGowen, AR Precision, and PAC-NOR.  By the end of April 2016, more than 1,000 .277 Wolverine barrels had been sold, with more than 2,000 by mid-November 2017.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}}  Barrels lengths include: 8.2, 10.5, 12.5, and 14.5 inch pistol; 16, 18, and 20 inch rifle.\n\n.277 Wolverine cases are easily made by the hobbyist reloader from plentiful and inexpensive 5.56\u00d745mm brass (shortened and resized). Extensive reloading data (including chronographed velocity, accuracy, and ballistic gel testing) is available.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}}  Ready-to-load brass and/or loaded ammunition is available commercially from several sources including: JB's Firearms, LLC and OutdoorShooterSupply.  Reloading dies and tools are available from Hornady, Lee Precision, Sheridan Engineering, CH4D, and Little Crow Gun Works.<ref name=\"MDWS-home\" /> The fire-formed .277 Wolverine case holds approximately 27.5-27.8 gr of water, compared to 28.5-28.8 gr for the parent case.\n\nIn October 2017, Starline produced 50,000 newly manufactured cases head-stamped \".277 WLV\" for MDWS; all were sold in under 72 hours of posting. Starline lists the .277 Wolverine on their website as a standard offering.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wolverine Starline Factory Brass|url=https://www.starlinebrass.com/brass-cases/277-Wolverine/|website=Starline Brass|publisher=Starline Brass|accessdate=2017-11-28}}</ref>{{secondary source needed|date=March 2019}}\n\n==Performance==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=March 2019}}\nThe .277 Wolverine has shown comparable performance to the 6.8 SPC with 110&nbsp;gr (7.13&nbsp;g) bullets, achieving similar [[Muzzle velocity|muzzle velocities]] of 2,500&nbsp;fps (762&nbsp;m/s) vs. 2,700&nbsp;fps (823&nbsp;m/s).  The smaller case of the .277 Wolverine (compared to the 6.8 SPC) is more efficient and has less [[recoil]] due to its smaller [[propellant]] load.  With lighter bullets, 80-90&nbsp;gr (5.2-5.8&nbsp;g), although slower than typical 5.56\u00d745mm rounds, the .277 Wolverine provides substantially increased energy due to greater mass. For example, 60-62&nbsp;gr (3.9-4.0&nbsp;g) bullets from a 5.56\u00d745mm round typically provide less than 1,200&nbsp;ft\u00b7lbs (1,627&nbsp;[[Joule|J]]) of [[kinetic energy|energy]], while 85-90&nbsp;gr (5.5-5.8&nbsp;g) bullets from a .277 Wolverine round provide over 1,500&nbsp;ft\u00b7lbs (2,034&nbsp;J) of energy (both at the muzzle of a 16-inch barrel).\n\nThere are always trade-offs between cartridge size, bullet diameter and weight, muzzle velocity, and energy on-target (at any given range). The .277 Wolverine will never replace larger high-power cartridges such as the [[.308 Winchester]] ([[7.62\u00d751mm NATO]]) or [[.270 Winchester]] for long range shooting; however \u2013 it outperforms the .223 Remington at typical hunting ranges and approaches the 6.8 SPC while using less expensive components (brass, magazines, bolt, less powder per load).\n\nThe following table provides comparative performance data for several factory cartridges in the mid-power AR-15 class:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Round\n! Bullet Weight\n! Barrel Length\n! Muzzle Velocity\n! Ballistic Coefficient(G1)\n! Energy at 300 yards\n|-\n| 5.56\u00d745mm (M855)\n| {{convert|62|gr|g|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|16|in|mm|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|2,900|ft/s|m/s|abbr=on}}\n| 0.304\n| {{convert|579|ft.lbf|J|abbr=on}}\n|-\n| 7.62\u00d739mm\n| {{convert|123|gr|g|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|16.5|in|mm|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|2,300|ft/s|m/s|abbr=on}}\n| 0.300\n| {{convert|633|ft.lbf|J|abbr=on}}\n|-\n| 300 BLK\n| {{convert|110|gr|g|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|16|in|mm|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|2,300|ft/s|m/s|abbr=on}}\n| 0.300\n| {{convert|622|ft.lbf|J|abbr=on}}\n|-\n| 300 BLK\n| {{convert|125|gr|g|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|16|in|mm|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|2,200|ft/s|m/s|abbr=on}}\n| 0.320\n| {{convert|644|ft.lbf|J|abbr=on}}\n|-\n| .277 Wolverine\n| {{convert|90|gr|g|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|16|in|mm|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|2,750|ft/s|m/s|abbr=on}}\n| 0.275\n| {{convert|736|ft.lbf|J|abbr=on}}\n|-\n| .277 Wolverine\n| {{convert|100|gr|g|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|16|in|mm|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|2,600|ft/s|m/s|abbr=on}}\n| 0.323\n| {{convert|754|ft.lbf|J|abbr=on}}\n|-\n| .277 Wolverine\n| {{convert|110|gr|g|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|16|in|mm|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|2,500|ft/s|m/s|abbr=on}}\n| 0.370\n| {{convert|837|ft.lbf|J|abbr=on}}\n|}\n\n==Applications==\nThe .277 Wolverine provides similar ballistic performance to the 6.8 SPC for accuracy, hunting (varmints to medium-game), target shooting, and home/personal defense.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} 277/6.8mm bullets are widely available from virtually all major and many boutique reloading component manufactures (e.g., Speer, Sierra, Hornady, Nosler, Barnes, Remington, Winchester, Woodleigh, Lehigh Defense, Hawk, etc.) in a wide range of bullet weights from 85 to 200 grains (5.5-13&nbsp;g) and styles useful in the .277 Wolverine - including lead-free practice, competition target, varmint, defensive, and game hunting.<ref>{{cite web|title=.270 Caliber, 6.8mm Bullets|url=http://www.midwayusa.com/270-caliber-68mm-277/br?cid=21737|publisher=Midway USA|access-date=2018-11-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170627182201/http://www.midwayusa.com/270-caliber-68mm-277/br?cid=21737|archive-date=2017-06-27|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe complete bolt carrier group (carrier, bolt, firing pin, and cam pin) and charging handle can be swapped between the original 5.56\u00d745 and the .277 Wolverine upper.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n\n==Comparisons==\nA very wide range of cartridges from diminutive [[.17 HMR|.17 rimfire]] to massive .50 caliber rounds have been used in AR-15 rifles. The .277 WLV provides medium bore (.277\") performance exceeding the parent 5.56\u00d745 cartridge and the [[.300 AAC Blackout|.300 BLK]] while approaching the power of the larger 6.8 SPC which requires larger cases and dedicated components (e.g., bolt and magazines). Per an interview with the cartridge's designer: \"I liked the performance of the 6.8 SPC and the versatility of the 300 Blackout. After researching both of them extensively, and having a lot of conversations with many, many experienced professionals and enthusiasts, I decided to move forward with a new cartridge design that would hopefully combine the attributes of both, and dismiss the deficiencies.\"<ref name=\"WPI-blog\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of rifle cartridges]]\n* [[Table of handgun and rifle cartridges]]\n* [[Glossary of firearms terminology]]\n* [[List of AR platform calibers]]\n* [[.300 AAC Blackout]]\n* [[6.8mm Remington SPC]]\n* [[7.62\u00d740mm Wilson Tactical]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{222remderivatives}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:277 Wolverine}}\n[[Category:Pistol and rifle cartridges]]\n[[Category:Wildcat cartridges]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox firearm cartridge \n|name=.277 Wolverine\n|image=\n|caption=\n|type=Rifle\n|origin= [[United States]]\n|designer=Mark Kexel, Mad Dog Weapon Systems, Inc.\n|design_date=2014\n|parent=[[5.56\u00d745mm NATO]]\n|case_type=Rimless, Bottleneck\n|bullet=0.277&nbsp;in (7.04&nbsp;[[Millimetre|mm]])\n|neck=0.3089&nbsp;in (7.85&nbsp;mm)\n|shoulder=0.356&nbsp;in (9.04&nbsp;mm)\n|base=0.377&nbsp;in (9.58&nbsp;mm)\n|rim_dia=0.378&nbsp;in (9.60&nbsp;mm)\n|rim_thick=\n|case_length=1.530-1.535&nbsp;in (38.86&nbsp;mm, trim) to 1.545&nbsp;in (39.24&nbsp;mm, max.)\n|length=2.26&nbsp;in (57.40&nbsp;mm) max. COAL (typical)\n|rifling=1:7 (subsonic/supersonic), 1:11 (supersonic)\n|primer=Small rifle\n<!-- Ballistic performance -->\n|is_SI_ballistics=\n|bw1=85\n|btype1=\n|vel1=2800\n|en1=1480\n|bw2=90\n|btype2=\n|vel2=2750\n|en2=1510\n|bw3=95\n|btype3=\n|vel3=2650\n|en3=1480\n|bw4=100\n|btype4=\n|vel4=2600\n|en4=1500\n|bw5=110\n|